<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Major South Korean Corporation Goes Broke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 20 (Xinhua) -- A second big corporate collapse in
two months shocked South Korea today, trapping both South Korean
financial markets and the government in a potential crisis.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of the Sammi Group came as the financial markets
and the government were reeling from the blow of the earlier Hanbo
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government must be extremely careful in
dealing with the fresh event considering the possible impact on an
economy in difficulty as well as the political situation, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
The Sammi Group, South Korea's 26th largest conglomerate, was
declared bankrupt on Thursday, unable to pay off an immense amount
of debt in principal and interest. It came only a day after its
flagship subsidiary, Sammi Steel Co., declared bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Total debt of the debilitated group amounts to 2.6 trillion won
(2.97 billion U.S. dollars), surpassing its total assets valued at
2.5 trillion won (2.9 billion dollars), according to company
figures.
</P>
<P>
Sammi Steel Co., a world leading speciality steel-maker, is
burdened with liabilities of 1.45 trillion won (1.64 billion
dollars), with an annual interest due of more than 100 billion won
(1140 million dollars), against assets of 1.53 billion trillion
won.
</P>
<P>
This is the second traumatic corporate collapse in two months.
The Hanbo Steel Industry Co., the number two steelmaker in South
Korea, had a January bankruptcy wrapped in a bribes-for-loans
scandal in which Kim Hyun-chol, the second son of President Kim
Young-sam, is involved.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government is anxious about the potential
impact of the Sammi collapse on financial markets. It is
considering effective measures to take to relieve possible
negative influences.
</P>
<P>
The more serious challenge, however, may come from the
opposition parties, which dubbed the Sammi event "the second Hanbo
loans scandal." They asked for a probe into the reported
connection between the Sammi Group and Kim Hyun-chol and Choi
Hyung-Woo, the latter a consultant of the ruling New Korea Party
and congressman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
