<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coach Fassi fies during World Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian figure skating coach
Carlo Fassi died in hospital during the world championships on
Thursday, it was announced thurday.
</P>
<P>
Heather Linhart of the United States team spokeswoman said,
Fassi, 67, coach of U.S. women's skater Nicole Bobek, complained
of stomach pains at the rink on Thursday morning and was taken to
hospital where he died later.
</P>
<P>
The coach, who was based in Lake Arrowhead, California, where
he was assisted in his coaching by his wife Crista, was the
European men's figure skating champion in 1953 and 1954.
</P>
<P>
He sprang to prominence as a coach when he trained American
Peggy Fleming to the world titles from 1966 to 1968 and to the
1968 Olympic title.
</P>
<P>
He also coached both 1976 Olympic gold medallists, John Curry
of Britain and American Dorothy Hamill, and 1980 Olympic men's
champion Robin Cousins of Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
