<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Ukraine Start Negotiation on Special Relationship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana and Ukrainian Foreign Minister Hennadiy Udovenko opened on
Thursday in Brussels their first round of negotiations toward the
formalization of the NATO-Ukraine relationship.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued after the talks, the two sides
stated that they were determined to conclude the NATO-Ukraine
agreement by the time of the NATO Madrid Summit in July, when NATO
will issue invitations to certain countries, most likely Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic, to join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting with Solana, Udovenko and Volodymyr Horbulin,
Secretary of the National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine,
also held a meeting with the 16 ambassadors of NATO member
countries at the "16 plus one" format.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting, Udovenko told the ambassadors that he
and Horbulin discussed with Solana the basic principles and
modalities of a formal document and that he was very satisfied
with the results of today's talks.
</P>
<P>
While stressing Ukraine's wish to build up "a strong, enduring
and effective relationship" with NATO,Udovenko stated that his
country would not apply for NATO membership at present because of
"lack of all conditions."
</P>
<P>
However, he said that "in the long run, accession to a
transformed and adapted NATO" was one of Ukraine's aims towards
NATO.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko said Ukraine "highly" appreciated NATO's declared
position that it has no intention to deploy unclear weapons on new
member's territory.
</P>
<P>
But he also stressed that one of the basic elements of the
future NATO-Ukraine document should be the confirmation by NATO of
the condition for any applicant country to complete the settlement
of all territorial and other problems with neighbors, including
Ukraine, which is trying hard to settle the border dispute with
Romania.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving NATO Headquarters, Udovenko told reporters that
NATO and Ukraine agreed to establish a working group to negotiate
the practical preparations for the document.
</P>
<P>
But he refused to comment in which shape the document would be
concluded, either a charter or a legally binding agreement, only
saying that "it was for further negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The minister also told the press that Solana will pay a visit
to Ukraine on May 7, on the occasion of opening a NATO Information
and Document Center in Kiev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
