<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Soars in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States Commerce
Department said today that America's trade deficit soared to 12.7
billion U.S. dollars for January because of higher oil prices and
rising auto imports.
</P>
<P>
The Department said the overall deficit in goods alone was 19
billion dollars, the highest in history, because of a 13.3 percent
jump in auto imports, led by a surge in shipments from America's
partners in the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Car imports from Canada increased 25 percent while imports from
Mexico rose 12 percent. Car imports from Japan were also up by six
percent.
</P>
<P>
It also said that foreign oil bill rose 5.2 percent to 6.8
billion dollars. Four-fifths of the increase should be attributed
to higher volume and the rest to rising prices.
</P>
<P>
The average price of crude oil rose for a seventh consecutive
month to 21.99 dollars a barrel, the highest level since the Gulf
crisis in January 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Department's statistics show that the overall deficit
climbed to 114.3 billion dollars last year, the worst performance
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the deficit will climb even higher this year as
the strength of the dollar softened U.S. commercial
competitiveness on both overseas and domestic markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
