<HEADLINE> Algerian Woman Militant Arrested in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian police have arrested an
Algerian woman suspected of aiding militant activities in Egypt,
the Interior Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
Jamila Maali al-Falaki, an Algerian, has been charged of
infiltration into Egypt to give instructions and funds to members
of the radical Islamic Jihad in Egypt, the Egyptian MENA news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
She was arrested on Wednesday when contacting an Egyptian
lawyer who also belongs to the Jihad, which is fighting the
government in a bid to install a strict Islamic rule in the
secular country.
</P>
<P>
The security authority said the woman was employed to revive
the movement's activities and mastermind terrorist attacks on a
number of personalities and vital installations in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
However, it said her every movement had been closely watched by
the state security bodies ever since she entered Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The woman received instructions from Yasser Tawfik Ali, a
much-feared Jihad leader taking refuge in Britain, it added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt said members of the group, which assassinated
ex-President Anwar Sadat in 1981 and attempted to kill former
Prime Minister Atef Sedki in 1985, have received military training
in camps run by its exiled leaders.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,070 people have been killed in a five-year-old
drive by Islamic militants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
