<HEADLINE> Chinese Youngsters Urged To Contribute to Peking Opera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Ding Guangen, a member of the
Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC) Central
Committee, has urged young performers to contribute more to Peking
opera, which is the high point of Chinese traditional art.
</P>
<P>
Ding spoke recently at a symposium sponsored by the Propaganda
Department of the CPC Central Committee and the Ministry of
culture for a training class of outstanding young Peking opera
performers.
</P>
<P>
Young actors and actresses should study more to improve their
work, Ding said, emphasizing that young people should carefully
study the Party's principles and policy on art and devote
themselves to the people and to socialism.
</P>
<P>
Performers are also asked to learn from culture, literature,
and other forms of art to enrich themselves and to perform better.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the training class should help players
practice more to improve their skill, and should include
traditional pieces and newer ones.
</P>
<P>
The education in professional ethics has also been stressed at
the symposium. Ding said that young people should respect the
older generation and learn from their spirit of devotion to the
art.
</P>
<P>
Reviving traditional culture and art is a major part of China's
socialist cultural and ideological progress, which falls on the
shoulders of the younger generation, Ding said, and youngsters
should strengthen their sense of responsibility and grasp every
opportunity to improve their skills.
</P>
<P>
The training class, which started last October, has 26
outstanding young performers from Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
