<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Causes Infertility, Says Nigerian Physician </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Tuberculosis (TB), a disease
commonly associated with pulmonary system, is one of the
causative factors for infertility.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Dr. Adedeji Ifederu head of the
Government Chest Hospital in Ibadan, a major city in southwestern
Nigeria, the Nigerian Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the medical expert, once the tiny mycobaterium
tuberculosis, which is the bacteria responsible to the infection,
enters the human body through the nostril, it can settle in any
part of the body to cause diverse forms of infection.
</P>
<P>
When the bacteria is disseminated through the blood system and
infects the fallopian tube in a woman or the testicle of a man,
it can lead to infertility if not properly treated.
</P>
<P>
However, Dr. Ifederu pointed out that TB infection does not
mean that the infected person will manifest the disease, because
most people have a natural resistance to the disease, especially
those who are not immuno-deficient.
</P>
<P>
A properly balanced diet provides good immunity against the
infection blossoming into full scale disease, he added.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he urged people to maintain balanced diet in their
daily food intake.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Health Organization (WHO) has launched a
new treatment system which combines a multi-drug system to a
careful monitoring of patients as a new action plan that can save
millions of lives from the drug resistance form of TB, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted WHO Director-General Hiroshi Nakajima as
describing the system as the biggest health breakthrough of the
decade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
