<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Djibouti Agree to Combat Illegal Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia and Djibouti agreed
to fight against contraband trade and cross border crimes along
their borders.
</P>
<P>
This was contained in a communique issued Wednesday at the
conclusion of the sixth meeting of the Ethio-Djibouti Joint
Border Administrative and Security Committee at Nazreth, 90 kms
away from Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the two sides have also agreed to provide
the necessary services in order to encourage legitimate trade
between the two peoples besides the reinforcement of the
implementation of agreements on extradition of offenders to deter
criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
Concerned about the emerging drug trafficking along their
borders, they have reached a consensus to devise a joint
mechanism in the fight against the social evil.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided to provide efficient consular services for
nationals of the two countries going to or residing in their
respective homeland.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the three-day meeting also
discussed ways of setting up mechanisms to foster better exchange
of informa- tion between border officials in a bid to overcome
problems that might surface in the process of discharging their
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting will be held in October 1997 in Tadjourah,
Djibouti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
