<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief, Mandela Optimistic About Zairean Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 20 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and South African President Nelson
Mandela expressed the view today that despite strong offensives
by rebel forces, there is still hope for a peace settlement in
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Cape Town after his talks with
Mandela, Annan said although the rebels were doing "very well on
the ground", no one in Zaire, including rebel leader Laurent
Kabila, was demanding secession or the breakup of the country.
</P>
<P>
"They want a change of leadership. That change can be attained
in many other ways, including through the ballot box," Annan
said.
</P>
<P>
The UN Chief expressed hope that following the on-going
preparatory summit in Nairobi, Kenya and the African Summit about
the Zairean crisis due to be held in Lome, Togo on March 26, the
warring Zairean factions would agree to a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
If a ceasefire was agreed to, the United Nations would have to
send peacekeeping troops to Zaire, Annan added.
</P>
<P>
South African President Mandela, who had talks with Zairean
rebel leader Kabila last month, also pointed out that Kabila had
insisted on meeting Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
"We are in the fortunate position that despite his successes
on the battlefield, he realizes the importance of negotiations,"
Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Zairean rebels, who began to launch offensives agaisnt the
government troops last October, had taken over one fifth of the
territory in the country.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the rebels were advancing on Lubumbashi,
the second largest city in Zaire, after taking Kinsangani in the
northeast last Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
