<HEADLINE> African Language Policies Need Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 20 (Xinhua) -- There is need for Africa to
reexamine its language policies with a view to rationalising and
adopting decisive national policies that promote unity, peace and
stability, a Zimbabwean cabinet minister said here today.
</P>
<P>
Opening a ministerial inter-governmental conference on
language policies in Africa, Chairman of the conference and
Zimbabwe's Higher Education Minister Ignatius Chombo said in
multi-lingual situations, it was necessary for countries to
clearly spell out those languages that were regarded as official,
those that were national but not official and those that were for
specific use.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly stated policies will enable African governments to
allocate more resources to the development of official languages
and use these languages in official communications," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added there was need for Africans to reexamine the use of
their own languages and accord them due recognition and status.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 50 of the 54 African countries are
attending the two-day conference which ends on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The conference is expected to highlight the use of African
languages as the best way of ensuring participation of Africans in
society as well as in the planning and management of development
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
