<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Explosion in Afghan City, One of Biggest in World's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Wednesday's explosion in
Jalalabad, an eastern Afghan city, is one of the biggest
accidental munitions explosions ever in the world's history, the
U.N. officials said today.
</P>
<P>
A United Nations assessment team today reported that the
explosion at a munitions store in Jalalabad, blew open a crater
measuring 50 meters in diameter and 10 meters deep.
</P>
<P>
Munitions and debris are scattered over a four-square-kilometer
residential and agricultural area, it said in a press release
issued by the United Nations Office for the Coordination of
Humanitarian Assistance (UNOCHA) to Afghanistan here today.
</P>
<P>
The team estimated that the volume of explosives that went off
could be as much as 200 tons.
</P>
<P>
According to latest casualty figures, about 30 were killed and
191 others injured in the blast. At least 80 of the injured were
in a serious condition.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth major munitions store explosion in
Afghanistan in recent years. Last year, stores exploded in
Kandahar and Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The UN agency is sending six teams of explosive experts to
Jalalabad to clear the area of unexploded munitions and debris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
