<HEADLINE> Zambian Copper Conglomerate Makes 12.46 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's state-owned
conglomerate, the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), made a
net loss of 19,722 million kwacha (about 12.46 million US
dollars) in the quarter ending December 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed in the ZCCM's report for third quarter
1996/97 financial year to March 31, 1997 available here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the loss made by the ZCCM in the same
quarter of the previous financial year was 2,865 million kwacha
(about 2.97 million US dollars) after taking into account of
exchange losses, interest, taxation charges, and other items.
</P>
<P>
However, the ZCCM report said that copper production for the
quarter at 67,022 tons was 3,692 tons higher than the 63,330 tons
in the same period of the previous year. Copper sales out of the
company's production for the quarter at 76,172 tons were 20,984
tons higher than the 55,188 tons sold during the same quarter of
1995. Sales, including metal bought-in, were 94,008 tons for the
quarter compared with 108,663 tons in the corresponding quarter
of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Cobalt production, at 1,116 tons for the quarter, was five
percent lower than the 1,175 tons produced in the corresponding
quarter of 1995. Sales of cobalt, at 1,126 tons were 52 percent
higher than the 743 tons sold in the quarter ending December 31,
1995.
</P>
<P>
The total sales revenue for the quarter was 358,512 million
kwacha, an increase of six percent over the 336,722 million kwacha
achieved in the same pf period of 1995. The increased revenue arose
from the improvements in sales tonnages for both copper (excluding
bought-in) and cobalt and the depreciation of the kwacha between the
corresponding period of the previous year and the period under
review -- from one US dollar equalling 965.69 kwacha to one US dollar
equalling 1282.69 kwacha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
