<HEADLINE> EC, Ukraine Reach New Steel Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators from the European
Commission(EC) and Ukraine have reached a new steel agreement that
will allow Ukraine to increase sales to the European Union of
certain iron and steel products up to the year 2001, the EC said
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement will ensure that Ukraine can enjoy stable growth
for one of its major exports to the European Union while gradually
bringing the competitive conditions of the Ukrainian steel
industry more into line with those of the European Union," the
Commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The new deal will cover certain iron and steel products under
the European Coal and Steel Treaty, such as coils, heavy plate or
wire rod.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which still needs approval by EU Ministers
and the Ukrainian authorities and should enter into force on 1
July this year, the quantitative limits for 1997 will be 233,154
tons, 10 percent higher than in 1996, rising by a further five
percent in 1998 and by 2.5 percent annually in 1999-2001.
</P>
<P>
The new agreement will follow the expiry, on June 30 this year,
of an earlier agreement covering the 1995-96 period, which allowed
Ukraine to increase its exports of products subject to quotas by
35 percent in 1995(140,833 tons) and 15 percent in 1996(161,958
tons). In addition, Ukraine could deliver 50,000 tons annually
to the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
But the Commission said Ukraine only used about 50 percent of
the limits in both years.
</P>
<P>
Total EU imports of Ukrainian iron and steel products - those
subject to quantitative limits and those where trade has already
been liberalized - rose from 660,000 tons in 1993 to 1.6 million
tons in 1995, according to the European Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation Falls to 2.7 pct in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Britain's annual rate of headline
inflation fell to 2.7 percent in February from 2.8 percent in the
previous month, giving a much-needed boost to the Conservative
government facing a general election on May 1, official figures
showed today.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) said today that the
government's preferred measure, the underlying annual inflation
rate, excluding mortgage interest payments, also fell last month
to 2.9 percent from 3.1 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The fall brought the underlying rate closer to the government's
target of 2.5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Lower food prices last month was the main cause for the fall in
underlying inflation rate, said the ONS. But clothing and footwear
prices in February rose 1.5 percent, and those of household goods
also staged a 0.8 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke hailed the fall as a
sign that the government is on course to meet its 2.5 inflation
target.
</P>
<P>
The figures were below economists' expectation of headline
inflation holding steady at 2.8 percent and were thought as easing
some of the pressure for an interest rate rise to tackle
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Strong average earnings figures and higher retail sales data
plus another big fall in unemployment total announced Wednesday by
the ONS had triggered fresh worries about higher interest rates in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
