<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Mammography Technique Developed in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Canada has developed a new
computerized mammography technology, which can make breast cancer
detection easier and at an earlier stage.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at Sunnybrook Health Science Center in Toronto have
developed a machine that makes high-quality digital images of the
breast, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The machine can find even the smallest tumor and calcium
deposits without using X-ray film, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
During the procedure, the breast is compressed between two
plates and subjected to an X-ray beam, much as in conventional
mammograms.
</P>
<P>
But instead of being captured on film, the image is stored for
display on computer monitors.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to film, the picture can be manipulated to magnify
particular sections that are considered suspicious. The result is
a sharper image that can be enhanced to highlight problem spots.
</P>
<P>
The technique will be especially beneficial for women with
so-called "dense" breasts, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
In addition, digitizing the images will allow them to be
transmitted along telephone lines or by satellite link to faraway
doctors for consultation.
</P>
<P>
The center, which has been working on the technology for the
past 12 years, plans to conduct two different trials over the next
year, which will involve 300 women.
</P>
<P>
It has also joined a North America consortium of universities
and corporations that will conduct a further test of the equipment
starting next year.
</P>
<P>
The first digital-mammography machines are expected to be
installed in Canadian clinics by the end of this year, the paper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0032 </DOCNO>
