<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nairobi Summit on Zaire Crisis Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The outcome of yesterday's
Nairobi summit on the Zaire crisis has been welcomed and the
United States has expressed its full support to the Nairobi peace
process for Zaire, Kenyan Foreign Minister Kalonzo Musyoka said
today.
</P>
<P>
Musyoka made the remarks at a news conference held at his
ministry here today, dismissing reports alleging that Kenya was
isolated in the peace process for Zaire.
</P>
<P>
According to the foreign minister, ambassadors of France,
Britain, Belgium and other countries expressed their welcome to
the conclusions of the summit which called for "a negotiated
settlement" to the escalating conflict in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the summit, George Moose, U.S. assistant
secretary of state in charge of African affairs who was an
observer at the meeting assured on behalf of the US government
its full support to the peace efforts initiated by Kenyan
President Daniel arap Moi, Musyoka further said.
</P>
<P>
He also rejected some allegations which claimed that certain
countries, namely Uganda and Rwanda, which had attended previous
two Nairobi summits held late last year, were excluded and Kenya
was isolated in the Nairobi peace process for Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Musyoka stressed that Kenya, Zimbabwe, Cameroun and South
Africa were mandated by all those countries represented at the
Nairobi Summit II to continue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, he also disclosed that Mohamed
Sahnoun, special envoy of the United Nations and the Organization
of African Unity, will fly tomorrow to eastern Zaire to meet
rebel leader Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun "will contact with Kabila on behalf of all of us and
President Moi to convey the conclusions of yesterday's summit to
him", the foreign minister added.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the one-day summit, which stressed the
urgent need for the implementation of the UN five-point peace
plan, also decided that the proposed Nairobi Summit III will be
held in Lome, Togo on March 25, just a day before an OAU special
summit on the conflicts in Zaire and other African countries.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that Kengo wa Dondo attended yesterday's
summit properly as prime minister of Zaire, adding that the vote
of some Zairean parliament members trying to remove Kengo from
his position did not meet the constitutional requirements.
</P>
<P>
The Zairean prime minister has left Kenya for Zaire, said
Musyoka at the news briefing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
