<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Syrian FMs Reject Israeli Final Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian and Syrian foreign
ministers today rejected Israel's offer to speed up the final
talks with the Palestinians and warned Israel not to play tricks
with the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouq al-Shara, after a meeting today, warned that the
Mideast peace march is now passing through "a very dangerous stage
and facing severe crisis because of Israel's policy.
</P>
<P>
On a recent Israeli proposal to wrap up talks on a final peace
agreement within six months, Moussa said it is merely a bundle of
"unspecific generalizations."
</P>
<P>
"They (the Israelis) should not consider themselves too smart,"
he told a press conference here. "We will not accept any promises,
generalities or sugar talk."
</P>
<P>
Israel rushed the Palestinians to resolve all the sensitive
issues including the future of Jerusalem and the Palestinian
statehood this year and set aside the 1993 interim autonomy deal
including three planned Israeli redeployment from the West Bank
and other commitments. Palestinians have turned down the offer.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the Oslo agreement remained the basis for peace
talks and that Israel could not alter it unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
"Let's maintain the peace process within its sound frame. Don't
try to play with this process and imperil it," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian foreign minister said at the press conference that
Arabs are disillusioned as Israel sent in bulldozers to Har Homa,
the site of a 6,500-unit new Jewish neighborhood in East
Jerusalem, where the Palestinians want to establish the capital of
their future state.
</P>
<P>
Shara said it is obvious that moving the bulldozers toward Har
Homa is "a tangible proof that (Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin)
Netanyahu neither wants peace nor does he seek to realize it."
</P>
<P>
"Netanyahu is working for something else quite contrary to the
peace process which we consider in danger," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak received a message
from his Syrian counterpart Hafez el-Assad on the peace process and
entrusted Shara with a reply message during their meeting today.
</P>
<P>
"We were unanimous that the peace process need to be maintained
according to the Madrid conference principles and the land-for-
peace framework," Moussa affirmed.
</P>
<P>
He said Arab countries will step up their coordinations
prior to the Islamic Conference to be held in Islamabad, the
Jerusalem Committee meeting in Rabat and during Arab League
meetings to confront the grave peace prospects.
</P>
<P>
On prospects for convening an Arab summit, Shara said contacts
are under way between Arab leaders to review the situation in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also met Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri at noon
and held talks with Palestinian President Yasser Arafat, who
arrived here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's Political Adviser Osama al-Baz is expected to meet
Dore Gold, Netanyahu's foreign policy adviser, this evening.
</P>
<P>
In his predeparture statement in Tel Aviv, Gold said he is
carrying some important "new ideas" to share with Egypt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
