<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York City to Take Stricter Measure on Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK March 20 (Xinhua) -- The New York Board of Education
on Wednesday voted to expel from school system any student 17 or
older who brings a gun to school or attacks someone with any
weapon.
</P>
<P>
The new policy, which is due to take effect in the fall this
year, is considered "the toughest" in the United States where most
other cities punish students by sending them to alternative
schools or by suspending them for up to a year.
</P>
<P>
The measure comes as reports of school violence are rising.
Last year from July through October, the school system reported
5,804 "serious incidents," which included weapons and drug
violations, up from 3,930 incidents in the same period the year
before.
</P>
<P>
The number of older students has risen in recent years as
dropout prevention programs have come more effective. There are
103,000 students 17 and over in New York City, roughly 10 percent
of the student body, according to figures provided by the New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
Growing concern over school violence nationwide has compelled
many school districts to adopt strict new zero-tolerance
policies against gun possession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
