<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Water Shortages Worsening Worldwide By Wang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 20 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations official today
said that one-third of the world's population will suffer from
chronic fresh water shortages by the year of 2025.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, Elizabeth Dowdeswell, Executive Director
of the U.N. Environment Program (UNEP), stated that the water
shortages had been worsening due to increasing demands by growing
populations, decreased quality of existing water resources and
accelerating requirements of expanding industries and
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued here today at a press briefing pointed
out that water shortages already exist in Africa, the Middle East
and parts of North America, Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Eightyeight developing countries where live about half of the
world population already "experience significant water deficits",
stressed the statement commemorating the 1997 World Watedr Day on
March 22.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official noted that UNEP had worked with governments,
its partner U.N. agencies and other organizations in developing
and initiating a number of major programs aimed at alleviating
the looming water crisis.
</P>
<P>
Accolrding to a UNEP report distributed at the press briefing,
the world populations will increase from the present 5.7 billion
to 8.3 billion in 2025, "making water shortage problems worse".
</P>
<P>
And much of this increase will be in the rapidly growing urban
areas of developing countries, many of which are already
experiencing serious water problems, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Another driving force which could make water problems worse
will be increasing consumption of food and industrial goods
produced with water, it said.
</P>
<P>
Irrigation already accounts for 70 percent of the water taken
from lakes, rivers and underground sources, and there will be
pressure to use more water to produce food for the increasing
population.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that some countries had made impressive
reductions in the amount of water needed for irrigation,
industrial and municipal purposes by using more effective water
management systems and better technologies.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, these gains have not reversed either the
general trend toward water shortage, nor the widespread decline
in water quality.
</P>
<P>
The report urged decision makers in the world to start from
now water resources projects to meet the needs of societies and
economies in 2025 because of the lengthy period of planning,
design and construction of large water projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer-banking Bugs Turn off Customers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 20 (Xinhua) -- As more Americans sign up for
banking and bill paying on computer, some banks' systems are
becoming overloaded -- causing delays and bounced checks.
</P>
<P>
The USA Today reported Thursday that the industry is
experiencing growing pains and is fixing the problems. But some
customers are losing patience and returning to traditional counter
banking.
</P>
<P>
Since NationsBank launched its personal computer banking
service a year ago, 320,000 customers have signed on. "We were
able to keep up with the growth until recently," said Smita Quinn,
PC banking manager. Customers of the system have repeatedly
encountered connection delays.
</P>
<P>
They sometimes had to wait up to 10 minutes to speak to a bank
representative by phone, according to the report. So NationsBank
curtailed its marketing push and added its call center staff.
</P>
<P>
Chase says it also is increasing its phone staff -- from 50
people to 150 by the end of April. The bank said it tried to
resolve PC banking problems, but many are beyond its control.
</P>
<P>
CheckFree, a large national payment processor, says it now
has ironed out the problems.
</P>
<P>
But it is too late, because some customers could not wait and
gave up PC banking.
</P>
<P>
To make up for the losses of some customers, the bank has
sent some customers flowers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
