<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: No Breakthrough, No Failure Occur in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Helsinki, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Though hopes for a breakthrough
in the discussion of the expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) during the two-day summit between U.S.
President Bill Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin, the
two leaders would certainly make progress in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin, accompanied by their respective foreign
ministers, arrived here today and are expected to have a full-day
talk, focusing on the alliance's enlargement on Friday.
</P>
<P>
On his arrival in Helsinki, Russian President foresaw a tough
fight over NATO enlargement. "President Clinton and I have
difficult and serious talks."
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Yeltsin's spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said
that Yeltsin would defend Moscow's interests "like never before"
during the summit.
</P>
<P>
On her arrival in Helsinki, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright today reaffirmed that NATO will implement its eastward
expansion plan as scheduled regardless of any opposition from
Russia.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the two-day summit, Yastrzhembsky said that if
the alliance's expansion becomes true, it will be the "strategic
mistake" and "worst" decision after the end of the Cold War and
the West will pay high price for it.
</P>
<P>
He said through an interpreter that NATO has no reasons at all
to expand since there is no more ideological confrontation
following the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
"There are none of reasons for NATO to move eastward," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The discussions of the NATO expansion has already undermined
the trust between Russia and the West built after the end of the
Cold War," he said, adding that they "have thrown shadows" over
the relations between Russia and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
"Russia's approach to NATO expansion will not change regardless
of any summits, bilateral meetings and negotiations,"
Yastrzhembsky told reporters.
</P>
<P>
NATO's move also undermines arms reduction negotiations between
Russia and the U.S.. The implementation of the START II treaty
has stopped while process of starting talks on START III is
slowing down, said Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
"The ultimate solution to the issue is the denial of taking new
members, or postponing acceptance of new members, " he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The firm positions on both sides have indicated that it is
almost impossible for them to make a deal on NATO's expansion.
The row will surely linger on after the summit.
</P>
<P>
However, Russian officials say that progress could be made in
arms control and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival here, Yeltsin said, "Let us not lose
the partnership we have established and developed."
</P>
<P>
Michael McCurry, the White House spokesman, told a news
briefing here today that the U.S. and Russia should proceed the
negotiations "in the spirits of partnership."
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky said that the summit is important to both sides
since it takes place after the two presidents haven't seen each
other for a long interval, and against the background that they
were both reelected not long ago.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents will review bilateral relations since the
end of the Cold War and the summit also offered a chance for them
to "lay down an outline for Russian-U.S. partnership in the 21st
century," Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
NATO's expansion will be decisive in building a new security
order in the 21st century. Clinton has made it one of his first
foreign policy priorities.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the U.S.'s goal is to dominate the European
affairs by enlarging NATO, getting more involved in the alliance
and then achieve its aim to "lead the world" in next the century,
or to build a one-polar world.
</P>
<P>
But Yeltsin has indicated that Russia's policy is meant to
create new world order of a multi-polar global arrangement. The
world must avoid the domination of one particular center of power.
</P>
<P>
The foreign policy differences will surely cause more troubles
and disputes in the future U.S.-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
But analysts say confrontation between the U.S. and Russia is
impossible. Russia needs the help of the U.S. in the field of
economy while the U.S. needs Russia's cooperation in building
Europe's security.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they analyzed that there will be no breakthrough in
the Helsinki summit, but the two sides will pledge to strengthen
partnership.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials say that Clinton has brought a package of
concessions to Helsinki to woo Russia and spur the ratification of
START II treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
