<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Warns of Increase in U.S. Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan today warned that there was an urgent need for
vigilance against inflation, sending a signal that the central
bank was ready to raise interest rates as a pre-emptive measure
against rising prices.
</P>
<P>
In testimony before the congressional Joint Economic Committee,
Greenspan said the U.S. economy shows a "quite favorable"
performance, but "demand has been growing quite strongly in recent
months." He worried about how long that could continue before
triggering rising prices.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan said it was critical for the Fed to act "ideally
pre-emptively" to keep inflation from getting out of hand.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's rate-setting panel, the Federal Open Market
Committee, will meet next Tuesday to consider raising short-term.
</P>
<P>
The Fed has not changed interest rates for more than a year and
it has not increased the funds rate since early 1995.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan said that at next week's meeting, Fed policy-makers
will try to determine whether a recent acceleration in
productivity gains is enough to keep rising wage pressures from
becoming inflationary.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the central bank would have to raise rates to
slow the economy if it determines that wage pressures are
threatening to outstrip productivity gains.
</P>
<P>
Economists expected the increase will come as early as this
month or in May at the latest.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan's remarks today unsettled financial markets. The Dow
Jones industrial average, slipping before Greenspan spoke, was
down 54 points by late morning as investors feared that higher
interest rates were on the way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Local Elections Start in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican parliament, after
long and fierce debates, today approved a governmental bill under
which the country's local autonomy elections will start in
November first in 33 municipals.
</P>
<P>
The bill was passed with 126 votes in favor from the ruling
Frelimo party and 113 against from the two opposition parties of
the Mozambican National Resistance (Renamo) and the Democratic
Union (DU).
</P>
<P>
A DU member abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
Among the 33 municipals are national capital Maputo and 10
provincial capitals in this southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Frelimo, or the Mozambican Liberation Front, insists on
gradual regional elections in bids to avoid turmoil, while its
rival Renamo wants the ballot to be cast simultaneously
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican President and Frelimo Chairman Joaquim Chissano
reached agreement with Renamo leader Afonso Dhlakama last October
that local autonomy elections can be held this year at any places
whenever conditions are ripe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
