<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-20 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Reiterates Palestinian Claim to Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat warned in Gaza this afternoon that
without Jerusalem, regarded by Palestinians as the capital of
their future state, there will be no peace in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian press service
based in East Jerusalem, Arafat issued the warning when addressing
the 88-member legislative Palestinian Council session. He noted in
the speech that Israel must know that it cannot play with the
issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader stated that Jerusalem is a red line
for Arabs, Muslims, Christians throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Arafat accused Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu of trickery
and conspiracy on the peace process, adding that the
irresponsible decision to build the Jewish settlement at Abu
Ghneim (Har Homa) undermines the entire peace process, as well as
security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Although Arafat appealed to Palestinians not to use violence
against the construction of the settlement in the Arab East
Jerusalem, hundreds of Palestinians launched a protest procession
in Bethlehem. They hurled stones and Molotov cocktails at Israeli
soldiers guarding Rachel's Tomb, a Jewish holy site in the
Palestinian self-rule city.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers responded with rubber bullets, tear gas and water
cannons. The confrontation lasted more than three hours, but no
one was injured. Palestinian police succeeded in preventing the
protesters from marching over the municipal boundary.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, apparently inspired by the start of construction at
Har Homa, five families of Jewish settlers moved into a home in
the Palestinian neighborhood of Silwan in East Jerusalem. However,
officials at the Prime Minister's Office claimed that their
action has nothing to do with the government.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai visited the Har Homa site
this afternoon warning the Palestinians not to use Friday prayers
at mosques to stir violence.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that Israel has received information to this
effect. But he added that the security forces are ready for any
eventuality. It is believed that he was apparently referring to
snipers and paratroops, and such hardware as tanks and
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
At today's Palestinian Council session, Ahmed Qrei' (Abu Ala)
was reelected President of the Palestinian Council. Ibrahim Abu
Al-Naja was elected First Deputy President. Second Deputy
President Mitri Abu Atta and Secretary of the Palestinian Council
Rawhi Fatouh retain their posts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
