<HEADLINE> Africa Must Play Role in Peace-keeping: UN Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 20 (Xinhua) -- African countries,
including South Africa, would have to play their role in
peace-keeping operations on the continent, visiting United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan said today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in Cape Town, Annan, former
Under-Secretary-General for peace-keeping operations, said he was
delighted that a group of African leaders had come together and
were working very hard to resolve the conflict in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the days when African nations and troops were
excluded and outsiders were brought in were gone. Therefore,
Africans must play their part in peace-keeping missions on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
If the U.N. Security Council decided to set up a monitoring
mechanism in the event of a cease-fire being brokered in Zaire,
"then we would welcome the participation of as many African
countries as possible", said the U.N. Chief.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan also expressed his support to the initiative
of establishment of an African Crisis Intervention Force, which
he said will be helpful for the continent.
</P>
<P>
The proposed African rapid response force was first mooted by
former United States Secretary of State Warren Christopher last
year, but was rejected by South African President Nelson Mandela,
who said the initiative should come form Africa, not outsiders.
</P>
<P>
However, Annan said Mandela and other African leaders should
not be concerned that anyone is trying to sideline them in the
move to createa such a force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
