<HEADLINE> SADC Signs Cooperation Pact With Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) has signed a general agreement of
cooperation with Belgium, the South African Press Association
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was aimed at steering and enhancing sustainable
development, community building and regional integration among
the 12 SADC countries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The accord, which included a joint technical committee
representing the Belgian Agency for Development Cooperation and
the SADC secretariat, was sealed in Gaborone, capital of Botswana
by SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuende and Belgian ambassador
L. Willems.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, the two parties said their future
cooperation should aim to strengthen SADC institutions and their
management capacity, and to expand the implementation of projects
with a regional or cross-border dimension.
</P>
<P>
SADC comprises Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius,
Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia
and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
