<HEADLINE> New Row Among British Parties on Sleaze Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen British members of
parliament(MP) out of 25 investigated on the cash-for-questions
affairs have been cleared by a interim Parliamentary Standards
Committee report published here today.
</P>
<P>
The report was out after opposition parties had alleged that
the Government was deliberately winding up Parliament early in
order to prevent the report being made public before the election.
</P>
<P>
But the report said the investigation into allegations that MPs
were paid by Mohammed Al-Fayed, the owner of London's Harrods
store, to ask questions in parliament on his behalf would not be
finished until next week.
</P>
<P>
Since Prime Minister John Major announced this week that
parliament would stop sitting on Friday that means the report on
the remaining 10 MPs cannot be published before the election.
</P>
<P>
The decision to defer a verdict on allegations of 10
Conservative MPs provoked a furious row between the government and
the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Tony Blair said there was no reason why the
report could not be published before the May 1 election.
</P>
<P>
Blair was joined by Paddy Ashodown, Liberal Democrat leader,
who accused the government of a cover-up, saying: "The
Conservatives have ended parliament as they started it --
breaking their promises, trying to con people and mired in
sleaze."
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives were furious, claiming that the row had been
deliberately staged to take the gloss of yesterday's sharp fall in
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Ministers described as slanderous the suggestion that the
election timing had anything to do with the report, and
Conservative Party chairman Brian Mawhinney accused Labor of
playing dirty politics.
</P>
<P>
"They only created this report scare...when they suddenly saw
the best economic news in terms of the dramatic fall in
unemployment, and they decided they had to have some story to take
it off the headlines," Deputy Prime Minister Michael Heseltine
said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties "look for a smear, look for a diversion
to stop the people of Britain focusing on the good news", he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
