<HEADLINE> Canada's Retail Trade Increases in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in Canada increased
1.4 percent in January after a small decline in December,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
Consumers in the province of British Columbia spurred this
growth by returning to stores in January after the harsh weather
in late December.
</P>
<P>
When the province is removed from the total, retail sales in
Canada increased by only 0.1 percent in January, the federal
agency said.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in January extends the pattern of flourishing
sales from September to November 1996, and more than offset the
small decline in December (0.1 percent down)," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
"The advances in the past five months contrast with the period
of slow growth from late 1994 to mid-1996," it added.
</P>
<P>
After a 5.4 percent decline in December, retailers in British
Columbia saw a 9.6 percent increase in sales in January than in
December. The figure is 9.7 percent higher than that of a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
"Increasing retail sales in January were broad-based with
increasing sales in six out of seven retail sectors," the agency
noted.
</P>
<P>
Only general merchandise stores saw a decline in sales (0.5
percent down), while other retail stores, food stores and the
automotive sector gained 6.4, 2.0 and 0.3 percent respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
