<HEADLINE> Canadian Exports Hit Record in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Canadian exports reached a record
17.1 billion U.S. dollars in the first month of this year, up 3.1
percent from December, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Exports to the United States grew the most, but there were
gains with all trading partners except the European Union," the
federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
In January, Canada's imports rose 7.2 percent to a record 15.6
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
This leaves Canada with a 1.5 billion dollar trade surplus for
January, compared with a surplus of 2.0 billion dollars in the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
Automotive exports made a strong comeback in January, jumping
ahead by nearly 23 percent. Cars were at the forefront of the
upswing, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, sales of metal ores, aluminum, organic
chemicals and agricultural products grew strongly on the Canadian
export side. Machinery and equipment, energy and industrial goods
pushed up its imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
