<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Discover Genetic Pathway to Most Colon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have identified a
genetic pathway that may play a role in the development of as many
as 90 percent of all colon cancers, the Johns Hopkins Oncology
Center announced today.
</P>
<P>
The pathway is associated with a tumor suppressor gene called
APC, identified by the Hopkins team in 1991 and found to be
mutated in 85 percent of all colon cancers, it said.
</P>
<P>
In the new studies, the Hopkins team and scientists in
University Hospital in Utrecht, Netherlands, found that the
mutation of APC results in the overactivation of two other genes
called B-catenin and Tcf.
</P>
<P>
"These three genes are part of a pathway -- an interconnected
series of genes that communicate with one another through the
production of proteins to regulate the growth and death of cells,"
said Kenneth Kinzler, co-researcher of the study.
</P>
<P>
"In colon cancers that do not have APC mutations, we found a
significant number of B-catenin gene mutations, which appear to
result in similar overactivation of the pathway," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kinzler and his colleagues believe the malfunctioning pathway
could be corrected with drugs known as "inhibitors" that block
B-catenin and Tcf gene -- the role the APC gene normally plays.
</P>
<P>
"It is much easier to block the function of B-catenin and Tcf
than to try to restore the missing function of APC. This is what
makes the discovery of this pathway so exciting," he said.
</P>
<P>
The findings, will also be reported in the March 21 issue of
the Science journal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meeting on Angola's Peace Process Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The 47th regular meeting of the
Joint Committee on Angola's Peace Process, which should have
opened today, was delayed for the third time due to disputes
between the Angolan government and the opposition UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, originally scheduled for March 14, was put off
due to the absence of members of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) till Wednesday, then Thursday. Now
it was set to be held on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The latest delay was made in accordance with the proposal of
the former rebel UNITA group, said U.N. envoy to Angola Blondin
Beye, who consulted with delegates from both sides in the
committee today.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, who consider Angola's peace process as now on a
"sensitive stage", called for all necessary measures to be taken
to remove obstacles to the peace process, said Beye.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the repeated mediation efforts by Beye and
representatives of the three monitoring countries -- the United
States, Russia and Portugal, differences remain great between the
Angolan government and the UNITA.
</P>
<P>
They differ on all the key issues for the peace process -- the
political status of UNITA Chairman Jonas Savembi, the
inauguration of UNITA lawmakers and the formation of the
government of national unity and reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also expected to discuss how to complete the
reorganization of the national united army and to set up national
administration structures in UNITA-controlled areas, local
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
