capital of Finland in his wheelchair for what promises to be a
contentious summit meeting with Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
And U.S. officials said sharp differences remain in the positions
the two presidents will take into a long meeting on the issues of
European security and arms control that dominate their agenda.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. is offering Russia a series of arms-control
concessions in an effort to win long-delayed ratification of the
START II nuclear-arms-reduction treaty.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.N. Security Council would grow to 24 nations from 15,
with five new permanent members, under a proposal that has been
submitted by the president of the General Assembly. But the new
members wouldn't receive veto power. Secretary-General Annan
backs expansion. 
</P>
