<HEADLINE> HK's Attorney General, ICAC Welcome Overturning of U.S. Court's Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Attorney General
and the Independent Commission Against Corruption (ICAC) on Friday
 both welcomed the judgment by the United States First Circuit
Court of Appeals which overturned an earlier ruling on former
tobacco company executive Jerry Lui Kin-hong who had been wanted
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. District Judge in Boston has granted a writ of habeas
corpus to Lui, who was wanted in Hong Kong to face bribery
charges, on the ground that the U.S. extradition treaty with
Britain would expire on July 1, 1997, and that after the date
Britain could not guarantee certain safeguards for Lui upon his
return to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The First Circuit Court of Appeals has reversed the grant and
found that there was sufficient evidence to support the Hong Kong
charges.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Jeremy Mathews noted that this judgment
removes the doubts and concerns arising from the earlier decision
concerning the future of Hong Kong's legal system. The move will
send a powerful message of reassurance of Hong Kong's extradition
arrangements after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the ICAC said: "The Commission welcomes
the decision of the U.S. Court of Appeals in favor of the
U.S. Attorney's Office, who are seeking Lui's extradition to Hong
Kong on behalf of the Hong Kong government. We hope Lui would be
returned to Hong Kong as soon as possible to face trial." 
</P>
</TEXT>
