<HEADLINE> Mobutu Heads Home, Appealing for Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Zaire's ailing president Mobutu
Sese Seko left France today for home after pleading for an
immediate ceasefire and national unity in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
Helped by his wife, the 66-year-old strongman, who underwent
fresh cancer treatment in a Monacan hospital from last Sunday to
Wednesday, boarded his private plane at southern France's Nice
airport and flew off to Kinshasa, the capital of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Thursday night, Mobutu called for a
ceasefire between government troops and Tutsi rebels, who have
seized around one-fifth of Zairean territories and were moving
towards the capital.
</P>
<P>
The president also proposed forming a national council,
representing every political party in Zaire, to find a peaceful
settlement of the country's crisis through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu's son, Nzanga, said on Wednesday that his father was the
only person who can make national unity possible.
</P>
<P>
Nzanga said President Mobutu should return home immediately and
find a diplomatic way to bring the country out of the present
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
But rebel leader Laurent Kabila refused Mobutu's call of
ceasefire later today.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu, the head of Zaire for the last 30 years, has spent most
of his time in Europe, mainly in his Riviera villa, since having
prostate cancer surgery last August in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
He returned to Kinshasa last December when he promised to
unleash a huge counter-offensive against the rebels, who had
already captured a large strip of territory in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
However, government troops failed to stop the rebels seizing
more land, including the key provincial capital of Kisangani on
Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
