<HEADLINE> International Officials Critical of Mostar Court Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- International officials on
Friday criticized a court trial in the Bosnian Croat-held part of
Mostar which virtually acquited policemen of attacking Muslim
civilians.
</P>
<P>
Colum Murphy, spokesman for Carl Bildt, quoted the High
Representative of Dayton peace accords as saying that the court
trial was "complete mockery and farce".
</P>
<P>
According to Alexander Ivanko, spokesman for UN International
Task Force (IPTF), the court in Western Mostar held only a
45-minute trial of the five accused policemen, without testimonies
from victims or witnesses.
</P>
<P>
The policemen were only charged with using physical forces and
rubber truncheons, although some of them were identified by IPTF
as using firing weapons against Muslim civilians on February 10,
which resulted in one death and two dozens of wounded.
</P>
<P>
At the end of trial, one officer was given one-year suspended
imprisonment, while two were sentenced to six-month suspended
imprisonment. The verdict said the sentences were suspended
before the policemen "were fighting for their country".
</P>
<P>
"These comments indicate that the court has no understanding of
professional police responsibilities in a peace-time democratic
environment, but is still entrenched in wartime rhetoric," Ivanko
said.
</P>
<P>
He called the verdict "disappointing and deeply troubling,
although not surprising for those who have been following the
latest development in Western Mostar". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
