<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Link Project in HK New Airport Core Program Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a major link
project in Hong Kong's New Airport Core Program has been
completed.
</P>
<P>
The 1.9-kilometer Rambler Channel Bridge carries the three-lane
 Route 3 Highway from Kwai Chung and across the Rambler Channel to
 feed into the Cheung Ching Tunnel on Tsing Yi Island. The bridge
is only the second in Hong Kong to be built using pre-cast
segments lowered into place by a launching girder.
</P>
<P>
This technique allowed a reduction of time in the construction
program as well as causing minimal disruption to marine traffic
during construction. It is also the first bridge in Hong Kong to
use external re-stressing, which will substantially reduce
maintenance costs.
</P>
<P>
The 1.6-kilometer Cheung Ching Tunnel carries the Route 3
Highway from the Rambler Channel Bridge, through Tsing Yi Island
and on to connect with the new Tsing Ma Bridge. The tunnel is the
 widest in Hong Kong and the first to carry three lanes of traffic
 in each of its two tubes.
</P>
<P>
Use of sophisticated "jumbo" drilling machines enabled
tunneling progress of an average of 35 meters per week, so the
excavation of the main tunnel was completed in 18 months, with
final excavation being completed two months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, all the expressways to the new town of Tung
Chung, including the Lantau Link, will be open to traffic and for
the first time people will be able to drive directly from Hong
Kong Island to Lantau Island.
</P>
<P>
The New Airport at Chek Lap Kok is scheduled to be put into
operation in April of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0085 </DOCNO>
