<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Official Says China And US Should Work Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Minister of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation Sun Zhenyu said here today that
China hopes to work with the United States to handle the Sino-US
trade balance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on a Sino-US Trade Balance white
paper, Sun said that China has made a great effort at cutting its
trade surplus with the US.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to open its markets, he said, and encourage
its enterprises to increase import from the US and welcome
investment from large US enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In reducing the trade imbalance, Sun pointed out, US companies
should make further efforts to increase their competitive edge in
the Chinese market to acquire a greater market share.
</P>
<P>
US banks should offer favorable terms to American companies to
give them a chance to get involved in bigger projects, he said,
and the US Government needs to decrease limitations on technology
exports to China. Only by doing so, he said, is it possible to
make full use of the potential and advantages of American
companies.
</P>
<P>
China had a surplus with the US in 1996 of 10.5 billion US
dollars. Sun said that an improper handling of the trade issue
will affect the normal growth of Sino-US ties.
</P>
<P>
Through joint efforts, statisticians of the two countries have
reached a consensus on reasons for the trade imbalance, he said,
and China is willing to continue consultations to address the
question of the imbalance and other trade issues.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, which was issued by the Information Office of
the State Council today, elaborates China's stand and views on the
Sino-US trade balance.
</P>
<P>
The paper's five topics are: "Soaring Trade Between China and
the United States"; "Statistical Differences in Sino-US Trade
Balance"; "Statistics Based on Rules of Origin Cannot Accurately
Reflect the Situation of Sino-US Trade Balance"; "US Export
Control Against China"; and "Sino-US Economic and Trade
Co-operation's Vast Vistas". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
