<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN first food shipments arrive in N. Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of foodstuffs
under the United Nations oil-for-food program has arrived in
northern Iraq Thursday, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
About 16 tonnes of chickpeas and 109 tonnes of vegetable oil,
part of contracts for 2,000 tonnes of chickpeas and 10,000 tonnes
of vegetable oil, were carried by eight trucks and crossed into
Zakhu in northern Iraq from Turkey.
</P>
<P>
It is the first consignment to enter Iraq since the imposition
of U.N. sanctions on Iraq in 1990.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. spokesman said that distribution of the foodstuffs will
start "as soon as practical arrangements are completed."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and Iraq signed the oil-for-food deal,
under which Iraq was allowed to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars of
oil for an initial six-month period to buy food and medicine for
its people hard hit by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions committee recently approved three contracts
under which Turkish foodstuff companies were allowed to export
foodstuff to Iraq at a total cost of 15 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi officials have complained about delays in food
deliveries.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published Thursday, Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz said "the Iraqi people have neither received
one loaf of bread nor a tablet of aspirin." The interview was
carried by the Arabic newspaper Asharq Al-Awsat, which is based
in London.
</P>
<P>
A shipment of rice from Thailand is heading to the southern
Iraqi port of Basra and is expected to arrive Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
