<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Blames Arafat For Tel Aviv Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu has laid the blame for a suicide bombing
attack in Tel Aviv this afternoon on the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) and its President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
A bomb went off inside a coffee shop in the center of
Tel Aviv, killing at least four people and injuring more
than 40 others, some of them seriously.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Ichilov Hospital, where the wounded have
been treated, Netanyahu said recent statements made by the PNA
had inflamed the situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli premier said that those who charged the Har
Homa building, a new Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem, was
responsible for the attack "were wrong," adding "that was not
the case."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat has condemned the suicide bombing attack,
which he termed as "terrorist incident," in Tel Aviv, saying
he was disturbed by the violence.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the condemnation in a telephone conversation with
Israeli President Ezer Weizman, shortly after the bombing attack
took place.
</P>
<P>
The explosion occurred around 13:45 p.m. local time
(1045GMT), at Apropo Coffee Shop at the corner of Ben Gurion
Street and Adam Hacohen, just one block from Dizengoff, where
a suicide bombing attack took place one year ago.
</P>
<P>
Israel Television quoted police sources as saying that
according to an identity card found beside a dead body, the
suicide bomber was from the West Bank village of Tzurif.
</P>
<P>
An identified man told the Israel Television that a member
of Hamas, the Islamic Resistance Movement, carried out the
attack, adding Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's policy was
responsible for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Following the bombing attack, the Israeli army immediately
imposed a total closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
barring Palestinians from entering into Israel.
</P>
<P>
The explosion occurred at a time when tension has been rising
between Israel and the Palestinians, after the construction of
a Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem started Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
