<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Marine Economy Maintains Rapid Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is estimated that the output of China's marine industry this
year will reach 310 billion yuan (about 38 billion US dollars),
and will hit 500 billion yuan by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the coastal areas of China, which
accounts for 13 percent of China's total area, have produced grain
to feed 40 percent of China's total population, producing 60
percent of China's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
China's marine industry has been developing rapidly since the
1980s, with traditional trades such as oceanic fishing,
transportation, and salt manufacturing taking the lead, and some
newly-booming industries such as sea water breeding, the off-shore
oil and gas industry, and seashore tourism following suit.
</P>
<P>
China has also begun to make headway in the fields of oceanic
energy development, deep-sea mining, the oceanic information
industry, and comprehensive sea-water use.
</P>
<P>
"The industry, however, still faces disadvantages such as
limited scale, outdated technological equipment, and little
tertiary industry," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
In the next 15 years, China will attach key importance to the
development of seashore and offshore areas. It will form the
structure of the oceanic industry with transportation, fishing,
oil and gas exploitation, and seashore tourism as its pillar
industries.
</P>
<P>
Close attention will be paid to the development of five coastal
areas, they are around Bohai, along the mouth of the Yangtze River
and the Hangzhou Bay, the southeastern coastal areas of Fujian
Province, the mouth of the Zhujiang River, and the Beibu Gulf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
