<HEADLINE> Dozens Of Palestinian Demonstrators Injured In Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 21 (Xinhua) -- While Tel Aviv was shocked by
an explosion, some 30 Palestinians were injured in confrontations
with Israeli soldiers near Beit Hadassa in Hebron today, according
to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian press service based in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, protesting Israeli construction of a new
Jewish settlement at Har Homa in East Jerusalem, threw stones at
Israeli soldiers guarding the religious holy site and Jewish
settlements in the largely Palestinian self-rule city, lightly
hurting four soldiers. The Israeli border police fired tear gas
and fired their gun in the air.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli military authorities imposed a curfew on the
area under Israeli control in the city.
</P>
<P>
Jibril Rajoub, head of the Palestinian Preventive Security
Service in the West Bank, came to the scene in an attempt to keep
order.
</P>
<P>
In Abu Ghneim (Har Homa), Israeli police dispersed crowds of
Palestinians who burned tires and tried to block the main road in
protest against the settlement construction there.
</P>
<P>
At a nearby open space, police prevented a number of Israeli
"Peace Now" activists from reaching the scene to express their
solidarity with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In the West Bank city of Ramallah, Palestinian residents held
a protest procession after Friday prayers. They made their way
for an Israeli army checkpoint, but were stopped by
Palestinian police halfway on the road.
</P>
<P>
In the explosion in down town Tel Aviv today, at least four
people were killed and more that 30 others wouned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
