<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin Get Closer on Europe's Security, Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin moved closer on NATO's
expansion during their first session of summit here today, a
Russian spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the first round of talks between Clinton and
Yeltsin, both spokesmen from Russia and the U.S. told separate
news briefings that the two presidents have more than two hours of
"intensive" discussion.
</P>
<P>
Russian presidential spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky told
reporters that a joint U.S.-Russian statement on Europe's security
could be issued at the end of the close-up summit meeting. "It is
too early to provide details on the exact contents of the
document," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. White House spokesman Michael McCurry said the two
presidents had a "very lively, very intensive" discussion on
Europe's security issues and arms control.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents spent two-thirds of the two-hour
"substantive conversation" on Europe's security, and one third on
the arms control, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Clinton and Yeltsin reiterated their
positions on the issue of the NATO expansion. Neither side has
made any concessions over the issue.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Clinton made it clear to Yeltsin that the
alliance's expansion will not threaten Russia while Yeltsin still
strongly opposes the plan.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents will continue their discussion later in the
day on the economic issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
