<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in South Korea Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in South Korea
rose rapidly in January and February this year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors put 1.24 billion U.S. dollars into 141
projects in South Korea in this period, four times higher than the
308 million dollars invested in the same period last year, the
Finance and Economic Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The investors were tending to pour more money into the
manufacturing industry with 850 million dollars going into this
sector so far this year, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has raised its investment in South Korea,
overtaking the United States in 1996 as the largest investor.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, South Korea has expanded the investment scope,
simplified procedures and amended investment laws in a bid to
absorb more foreign capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Claims About Palme's Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 21 (Xinhua) -- A report provided by Swedish
lawyer Pelle Svensson claims that Lars Tingstrom -- known as "The
Bomb Man" -- planned the murder of former Swedish Prime Minister
Olof Palme.
</P>
<P>
The press said here today that the report would lead to new
interrogations.
</P>
<P>
The bottom of the Klara sea canal in central Stockholm would be
searched as Svensson claimed, with reference to Tingstrom, that
the weapon used was thrown in there after the murder.
</P>
<P>
Chief District Prosecutor Jan Danielsson said he did not doubt
that Pelle Svensson was truthful, but it was another question how
much credit one should give to Tingstrom's report.
</P>
<P>
Tingstrom, who was serving a lifetime sentence for bomb
attacks, claimed shortly before he died in 1993 that he planned
the murder of Palme, and that Christer Pettersson was involved in
the plans. Pettersson was previously found guilty of the murder
but later acquitted by the Svea Court of Appeal.
</P>
<P>
"The Bomb Man" Tingstrom allegedly gave the information to
Pelle Svensson who was not allowed to reveal it within 10 years of
the murder.
</P>
<P>
Jan Danielsson said that at the moment the question of asking
for a reopening of the Pettersson case was not being considered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
