<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Calls for Resumption of Peace Talks With MILF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government today
called for the resumption of informal peace talks with the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) to end hostilities following the
resurgence of conflicts in Buldon, Mindanao, last week.
</P>
<P>
Speaking over radio in Cotabato City, Mindanao, government
negotiator Fortunato Abat suggested that a government-MILF meeting
be held before the third round of peace talks scheduled for April.
</P>
<P>
"Our cessation technical committees should meet on March 24-25,
just before the Lenten days. They (really) have to sit down and
instead of blaming each other, they should do something positive
(about it)," Abat said.
</P>
<P>
The March 15-16 mortar shelling between the MILF and government
forces in Buldon killed 11 civilians, wounded three government
soldiers and displaced hundreds of families in Buldon.
</P>
<P>
Abat also suggested that at the next week's meeting, a "joint
investigative committee" should be formed to put an end to the
"trading of accusations" by the government and the MILF.
</P>
<P>
Soon after Abat's radio speech, the MILF, which earlier
threatened to withdraw from the peace talks, has reportedly agreed
to the government proposal but singled out a certain condition
before negotiations would resume.
</P>
<P>
"We agree that the meeting be held immediately, but we need an
assurance that something official should come out from this
meeting," said Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice-chairman for political
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar said that instead of just talking over the telephone on
the problem between him and Abat, the cessation of hostilities
committees should draft "something final".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
