<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin Get Closer on Europe's Security, Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin moved their positions closer
to each other during their first session of summit here today, a
Russian spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Both Russia and the U.S. noted that the discussions are "very
intensive."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, U.S. White House spokesman Michael McCurry said the
two presidents had a "very lively, very intensive" discussion on
Europe's security issues and arms control.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents spent two-thirds of the two-hour
"substantive conversation" on Europe's security, and one third on
the arms control, Michael McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot report to you at this point they have reached
agreement because this is a discussion ...as the day is going on,"
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents will continue their discussion in the
afternoon on the economic issues. 
