<HEADLINE> Australian Troops on Alert over PNG Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Australian forces were today
placed on standby to help evacuate Australian citizens if the
crisis in Papua New Guinea (PNG) worsened which was sparked by
sacking of the chief of the defense force in the south Pacific
nation.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard confirmed that some troops had been
placed on a higher state of readiness. However, he said "it was in
response to a routine determination by the head of defense force
General John Baker."
</P>
<P>
Howard told reporters that he believed the situation in PNG was
unstable but may be improving, "The impression is that things are
domestically a little calmer today than what they were yesterday."
</P>
<P>
The government source said Australian troops were not preparing
help the PNG police restore peace in that country.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Port Moresby, the mercenary force
hired by the PNG government, totaling 61 persons, left the country
tonight on a chartered air jut for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Prime Minister Julius Chan said "the departure
of the mercenaries was natural consequence, they are no longer
needed so there is no need for them to be here."
</P>
<P>
The contract between the PNG government and Sandline
International (a British firm) was released in Port Moresby today,
indicating that 70 mercenaries would be employed in the operation
against the Bougainville secessionists.
</P>
<P>
Julius suspended the contract Thursday and also announced a
commission of inquiry into the affair.  
</P>
</TEXT>
