<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Egyptian Newspaper Critical of US Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- A leading Egyptian newspaper voiced
today sharp criticism of the U.S. Mideast policy, urging
Washington to play an impartial role to salvage the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahram, the most influential daily in the country and the
Arab world as a whole, said in an editorial that the U.S. Mideast
policy "now faces dangerous challenge in the peace process because
this partial policy cannot be accepted by the Arab countries."
</P>
<P>
"What happened recently in Jerusalem and the Security Council
confirms that Washington did not only monitor and watch the
incident but gave its blessing and encouraged Israel through
protecting it at the Security Council and preventing any
international condemnation," the Arabic daily said.
</P>
<P>
It was referring to the U.S. veto early this month of an
Security Council draft resolution demanding Israel stop its
settlement construction drive in the disputed East Jerusalem. The
U.S. move has angered the Arab world and hurt its credibility in
the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
Washington joined European countries last week at a Gaza
conference in a bid to appease the protesting Palestinians. But
Israel rejected all outside pressure and went ahead with its plan
for building 6,500 housing units in Har Homa, or Jabal Abu Ghneim.
</P>
<P>
Since Israeli workers, protected by soldiers and policemen,
broke ground at the construction site Tuesday, Washington has made
no more comment on the sensitive issue, which seems to be
overshadowed by a Helsinki U.S.-Russian summit.
</P>
<P>
"The question now is until when will the American silence
last?" asked the newspaper, adding the silence would encourage
Israel to pursue its policy.
</P>
<P>
"The only way before Washington is to confirm to the world that
it is most serious in practicing the role of mediation and stand
against Israel to compel it to abide by the peace process," the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper made the criticism about a week after Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak returned home from an official visit to
Washington, where he tried to secure US support for the Arab
efforts to stop Israel from building more Jewish houses in the
occupied land, especially in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton defended the US veto at the Security
Council but reiterated it did not mean Washington was in favor of
the Israeli settlement policy.
</P>
<P>
Unsatisfied with the US explanation, the Arab press came out
with harsher words towards Washington, reflecting growing public
frustration over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
President Mubarak warned Wednesday that the Middle East is
facing a most serious crisis in 20 years and his Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa accused Thursday Israel of killing the Middle East
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
