<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Take 30,000 Immigrants Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Government hopes
to sustain immigration into the Republic at a rate of 30,000
people a year in order to help meet the country's shortage of
talent, the local television reported today.
</P>
<P>
The television report said that Singapore Deputy Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong revealed this when he spoke to the Singapore media
at the end of his visit to New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Sharing with New Zealanders on how Singapore remained
competitive and engaged in Asia despite having a small population
base, Lee said one way was by supplementing talent with qualified
people from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Last year, there were about 5,000, more than the usual number
of immigrants, being taken in, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The increased numbers were from India and overseas Chinese
students who had heard that Singapore was a good place to live and
work in, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy Prime Minister also said that another way to
maximize talent was through education. He said that the recent
University fee changes in Singapore were made to encourage more
students to take up engineering and the sciences.
</P>
<P>
He said there were still more to be done to encourage students
to take up sciences when they were in school and added that the
Government would like to see the percentage of girls in these
courses rise from about 25 percent now to 30 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
