<HEADLINE> Mozambique, S. Africa Signs Memorandums on Dam, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique and South Africa
signed here Thursday two memorandums of mutual understanding
under which they will cooperate in building a dam and an aluminum
refinery in Mozambique in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The 2500-megawatt dam will be built on the Zambeze River, 70
kilometers downstream from the Cahora Bassa hydropower station
with an installed capacity of 2075 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The aluminum refinery with an annual production of
245,000 tons will be constructed near here, the Noticias reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The documents were signed by Mozambican Minister of Mining
John Kachamila, Mozambican Minister of Industry, Commerce and
Tourism Oldemiro Baloi on one hand and South African Minister of
Mining and Energy Phanel Maduna and South African Aluminum
Company (ALUSAF) President Robert Barbour on the other.
</P>
<P>
The signing indicates the willingness of the two sides to
strengthen their cooperation and the regional integration, said
Kachamila.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the aluminum refinery in Mozambique will
promote the industrial development in South Africa and the whole
southern African region as well, Maduna noted.
</P>
<P>
The industrial advance in Mozambique will be meaningful for
other regions in Africa as the economic stride might start from
southern Africa, Maduna said. enditem








