<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dr. Sex Hotline Popular Among HK Youths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Sex Hotline is popular
among Hong Kong youths with more than 60 percent of the callers at
the age of 20 or below, a survey showed today.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen percent of the callers are even at the age of ten or
below.
</P>
<P>
The around-the-clock hotline, operative via the interactive
voice response system, has been inundated with calls from the
sexually confused since its launch in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 people dialed the number as of February 1997,
the survey showed.
</P>
<P>
"We are surprised at the number of calls," Hong Kong Sex
Education Association (HKSEA) President Li Man-chin said.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the AIDS Trust Fund and the Health Care and
Promotion Fund, the hotline is organized by the HKSEA and the
Department of Health to help young people to acquire positive
understanding of and develop proper concepts about sex-related
issues.
</P>
<P>
"They really want to know about sexual acts and behavior --
what sex is -- because they can't get the information from
school," Li said.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the callers were male, while 90 percent
chose to listen to messages in Cantonese.
</P>
<P>
The recorded messages on the hotline cover six areas:
physiological, psychological and behavior aspects of sex, myths
about sex, sexually transmitted diseases, love and marriage,
pregnancy and contraception, and sex and law.
</P>
<P>
The hotline now employs three languages: Cantonese, English and
Putonghua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
