<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Greets Bright Future: TDC Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's return to her
motherland will ensure the territory more vitality in its
development, said Victor Fung, chairman of the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Fung said, "As a Chinese, I am
looking forward to Hong Kong's handover with the approaching of
the day of June 30."
</P>
<P>
He said, "My confidence in Hong Kong's future arises from the
smooth transition in Hong Kong's political sector and the momentum
in its economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"I trust Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), for what he has done in the
past few months proved that he could lead Hong Kong into smooth
transition," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that with the support of the Chinese central
government, the principles of 'one country, two systems', 'Hong
Kong people governing Hong Kong' and 'high degree autonomy' will
be realized in the HKSAR," he said.
</P>
<P>
On economic issue, Fung said, Hong Kong's return will bring it
more opportunities to tap its potentials and enhance its
competitiveness in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 17 years, Hong Kong has benefited greatly from
the economic reforms and opening up in the Chinese inland areas,
he said.
</P>
<P>
As the largest overseas investor in the inland areas, the
Hong Kong-funded projects have reached more than 150,000 there
with about 50,000 manufacturing-oriented enterprises.
</P>
<P>
From 1979 to 1995, the total contracted investment from Hong
Kong investors in the inland areas reached 233.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Hong Kong's investment has turned to
large-sized infrastructural projects including highways, ports and
power stations.
</P>
<P>
With the opening of the service trade market in the Chinese
inland areas, Hong Kong expects to increase their investment in the
sectors of finance, retail sale, real estate and
telecommunications, Fung said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he said, Hong Kong and the Chinese inland
areas are also the largest trade partners to each other. In 1996,
the trade value of the two sides reached 134.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"More than half of the cargoes of the Chinese inland areas
shipped overseas passed Hong Kong," he said, adding that Hong
Kong's transshipping role for the inland areas will be
strengthened after 1997.
</P>
<P>
AS for TDC, Fung said, two roles are expected to be enhanced
after Hong Kong returns to China.
</P>
<P>
"In market promotion, TDC has set up 51 representative offices
in 34 countries and regions in the world and it has a worldwide
trade web on computer-linked net, which will be a useful mean for
the enterprises in the mainland to enter the international
market," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong can also serve as a training center for inland
enterprises to learn international business and community
management involving finance and securities, commercial and
industrial operations, effective administration and service
trade," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
