<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Posts, Telecommunications Corp. to Split </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation is scheduled to be replaced with
four independent institutions, according to the latest issue of
the Kenya Gazette.
</P>
<P>
The gazette said that the Communications Commission of Kenya,
the Telkom Kenya company, the Postal Corporation of Kenya and the
National Communications Secretariat will be established.
</P>
<P>
It stated that two bills published by Kenya's Attorney-General
Wako proposed that the commission would serve as the ultimate
regulatory authorities with powers to supervise and licence the
flow of information systems in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Wako noted that the bills would enable the liberalization and
privatization of the postal sector in order to attract capitals
from the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Daily Nation today reported that the bills
came in the wake of intense lobbying by American
telecommunication giants -- Miscrowave Communications
International and American Telephone and Telegraph Inc.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the two companies are "anxiously waiting
to get a share in the Kenya information network."
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the Kenyan government approved the sale of
five parastatal companies to speed up its privatization program.
</P>
<P>
Last year Kenya agreed on a 220 million U.S. Dollars aid plan
under the International Monetary Fund (IMF) soft-loan Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility.
</P>
<P>
The first disbursement of 37 million Dollars was issued in
1996 and the second one which was due in November last year has
been delayed for three months because of what the IMF sees as a
slow progress on privatization.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that an IMF review mission was not completed
because a privatization timetable for the Kenya Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation was not presented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
