<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, Russia Sign Agreement on Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Russia signed here Thursday
night an agreement on economic and trade cooperation especially in
oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Russian Minister of Fuel and Power Peotr Rodionov and
Iraqi Oil Minister Mohammed Rashid announced in a joint press
conference after the signing ceremony that the two countries would
cooperate in oil exploration, agriculture, industry and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, signed by Rodionov and Rashid, the two
countries have agreed to jointly develop two new oil fields in
southern Iraq, which are expected to produce 100,000 barrels of
oil per day.
</P>
<P>
Russia also agreed to provide 100,000 tonnes of rice and 50,000
tonnes of sugar and other foodstuffs to Iraq in exchange for oil within
the framework of the "oil-for-food" program.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under trade embargo imposed by the United nations
since 1990 when it invaded Kuwait. The ministers of the two
countries did not specify when and how they would carry out the
cooperation plan.
</P>
<P>
Rodionov arrived here on March 16, heading a delegation of 80,
the biggest since the Gulf war. He concludes his visit to Iraq
today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
