<HEADLINE> Mideast Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish cement consumers have called for measures
against cement market monopoly following privatization of most of
the countries' cement plants.
</P>
<P>
Sami Sari, chairman of the Turkish Construction Contractors'
Union, told the local newspaper Daily News Thursday that the
authorities have failed to introduce relevant measures to ban the
formation of cartels by the new owners.
</P>
<P>
Cement prices have been raised 12 times since the Beginning of
this year, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's foreign currency reserves attained an
all-time high of 13.974 billion US dollars in February, an
increase of 1.182 billion dollars over the previous month,
according to bi-weekly Israel Business today.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Israel reported earlier this month that the
country's reserves had risen by close 2.5 billion dollars, or 22
percent, since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Lebanon have settled a dispute over Beirut's
ban on imports of Egyptian potatoes, according to the local daily
The Egyptian Gazett today.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Al-Hariri told reporters
Thursday that "there is no economic tension."
</P>
<P>
Lebanon had angered Egypt by banning the imports to protect
home-grown produce. Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said
Sunday that countermeasures might be in order.
</P>
<P>
-- Egypt and Belarus signed Thursday two agreements on
economic, technological and technical cooperation, which were
expected to double trade value between the two countries in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Belarus Foreign Relations Minister Michael Marintchi
expressed interest in jointly producing passenger motor vehicles
with Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
