<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin Hope for a Deal Despite Disagreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Helsinki, March 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin met here today, hoping that they
could strike a deal despite their disagreements on the expansion
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"We must find constructive approaches and compromises," Yeltsin
said prior to the meeting, which took place at the Finnish
presidential residence.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who emerged from a white van, said the U.S. and Russia
have to approach each other and resolve their differences by
making compromises.
</P>
<P>
"I think we'll work something out," Clinton said. "I think he
(Yeltsin) really came here to do business."
</P>
<P>
The two presidents are expected to focus on NATO's expansion,
which is Washington's number one foreign policy priority, but
strongly opposed by Russia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin met "in a spirit that is open and candid
and realistic in dealing with some of the differences that exist,"
according to the White House spokesman Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, who arrived here Wednesday, were accompanied
by their respective foreign ministers while they are meeting.
</P>
<P>
On his arrival in Helsinki, Russian President promised a tough
fight over NATO enlargement. "President Clinton and I have
difficult and serious talks."
</P>
<P>
Also Thursday, Yeltsin's spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said
that Yeltsin would defend Moscow's interests "like never before"
during the summit.
</P>
<P>
On her arrival in Helsinki, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright reaffirmed that NATO will implement its eastward
expansion plan as scheduled regardless of any opposition from
Russia.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the two-day summit, Yastrzhembsky said that if
the alliance's expansion becomes true, it will be the "strategic
mistake" and "worst" decision after the end of the Cold War and
the West will pay a high price for it.
</P>
<P>
The firm positions on both sides have indicated that it is
difficult for them to make a deal on NATO's expansion. However,
Russian officials say that progress could be made in arms control
and the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival here, Yeltsin said, "Let us not lose
the partnership we have established and developed."
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials say that Clinton has brought a package of
concessions to Helsinki to woo Russia and spur the ratification of
START II treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Host 15th World Petroleum Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The 15th World Petroleum Congress
(WPC) is slated to be held in Beijing between October 12 and 16
this year, with an expected participation of about 3,000
representatives from over 80 countries throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the upcoming WPC will be "technology and
globalization -- leading the petroleum industry into the 21st
century", according to Wang Tao, chairman of the Chinese
Organizing Committee of the 15th WPC.
</P>
<P>
The chairman noted that the 5-day conference consists of 6
plenary addresses, 21 panel discussions, 10 review and forecast
reports and a ministerial forum. In addition, some 95 papers will
be reported to the congress and 240 papers will be posted up for
academic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
All the reports and papers will focus around the issues of oil
exploration, development and drilling, processing technology,
natural gas, oil and gas reserves, environment and safe
production, as well as oil and gas transportation, the chairman
added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the oil experts throughout the world will conduct
exchanges on the latest scientific and technological results
concerning oil production from different aspects and perspectives.
</P>
<P>
Still, they will discuss the chances and challenges facing the
world petroleum industry in the upcoming 21st century.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese Organizing Committee of the 15th WPC,
the congress has drawn the attention and support from oil sectors
across the world. The Exxon Corp of the United States today made a
donation of 400,000 US dollars to the congress and some other
overseas oil companies have also joined in the effort.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
