<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Mekong River Delta Gathers Bumper Rice Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 21 (xinhua) -- Farmers in the Mekong River Delta,
Vietnam's largest rice producing area, have a bumper winter-spring
rice harvest, achieving an average yield of six to seven tons per
hectare, and even up to nine tons in some areas, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
An Giang Province, the biggest rice producing province in the
delta, harvested about 1.36 million tons of rice, a 100,000-ton
increase over last year.
</P>
<P>
Can Tho Province reached the one-million-ton mark for the first
time, with an average yield of six to 6.1 ton per hectare.
</P>
<P>
The present harvest came one month late because of heavy floods
and slowly receding water at the beginning of the crop season. As
a result, the follow-up summer-autumn rice crop will be one month
later than usual.
</P>
<P>
The flood season in the area lasts for three months beginning
in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
