<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador: No Great Change Expected in Greek-Turkish Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Despite the recent spring
atmosphere in relations, a senior Greek diplomat ruled out major
change in the long-standing tension between the two countries,
local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the English paper, Greek
Ambassador to Turkey Dimitrios Nezeritis said Athens always
supported a Western-oriented Turkey because stability in the
region was important for Greece, but people should not take it
for granted that great change could be expected in Greek-Turkish
relations.
</P>
<P>
Nezeritis' remarks came following the latest positive
statements by Greek leaders on the issue of Ankara's bid for
full European Union (EU) membership.
</P>
<P>
In response to an earlier statement by EU Christian
Democrats that Turkey could not be a member of the EU
because of its Muslim culture, Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis said Turkey was a part of Europe. And Foreign Minister
Theodoros Pangalos voiced that Europe's reluctance to embrace
Turkey due to its religion identity was tantamount to fascism.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Turkish Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Tansu Ciller sent congratulations to Greece and said she hoped
for dialogue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Nezeritis told the paper that he understood Ankara was
pleasantly surprised at the recent remarks from the Greek
government, adding that Athens supported Turkey's European
orientation only because of the geographic reason.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is a neighbor of our country and no third country
can come between us," said the Greek ambassador, indicating that
security enjoyed priority in the relations between Greece and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
When asked why Greece blocked EU funds for Turkey,
Nezeritis noted that Greece regretted the long-term tension in
bilateral relations and the Turkish position in the last crisis,
which made it impossible for Athens to take a completely
supportive stance.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey are traditionally rival countries because
of the controversial Agean Sea and Cyprus issues. The two
countries came to the brink of war at the beginning of last
year in a dispute over the sovereignty of the uninhabited
small island of Imia (Kardak or Ikizce for Turkey).
</P>
<P>
The tension between the two countries also drew international
focus following the Greek-backed Cyprus government's decision to
buy anti-aircraft missiles from Russia early this year, leading
to a visit of Turkish Navy warships to northern Cyprus aimed
at showing Ankara's military support to the Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
"We have tried from the beginning to keep the latest
crisis self-contained so it could be dealt with easily. This
is why we suggested a step by step approach to these
issues," Nezeritis said.
</P>
<P>
As for the press reports that Greece wanted to see Turkey
in the EU because it thought the bilateral problem could be
solved this way, the ambassador said," Once Turkey becomes a
full EU member, the problem would be settled through the
interference of the EU. I don't think we need to make this
issue more complicated." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Purchases US-made Telecom Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinasat, a key local satellite
operator and China National Posts and Telecommunications Appliance
Corporation, announced here today to buy a large telecom satellite
made by Space Systems of US-based Loral Corp.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was held at the Great Hall of the People
today.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed "Chinasat 8", the satellite is designed to meet the
needs of China's modern telecom satellite network.
</P>
<P>
The satellite has a total of 52 transponders with 36 of which
are C-band and the rest Ku-band.
</P>
<P>
The orbit slot of the satellite is 115.5 degrees East
longitude. The broadcasting coverage can incorporate all of
China and several neighboring countries and regions. Due to be
delivered into orbit by the end of 1998, its designed service life
is more than 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be operated and managed by Chinasat.
</P>
<P>
Sources from China's Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications
said that the use of the new satellite can meet the increasing
demand of China's public satellite telecom network, expand the
coverage of the country's national telecom net, and also enable
other domestic organs involved in satellite telecom or
broadcasting and TV to offer more diversified services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
