<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Sell Armored Vehicles to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has agreed to sell
211 armed vehicles to Malaysia to help the southeastern Asian
country enhance its defense capabilities, defense sources said.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted defense sources as
saying that Turkey and Malaysia had agreed to sign an arms
deal for the sale of 211 Turkish armed vehicles with a total
value of 250 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish team made up of defense officials went to Kuala
Lumpur, capital of Malaysia, for the negotiations of this
contract last month.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Malaysia intended to purchase different
types of armed vehicles from Turkey, which was capable of
producing four separate models.
</P>
<P>
Turkey produces its armored vehicles under a joint project
with the U.S. firm FMC. recently, Turkey also signed a 26
million U.S. dollar deal with the French firm, GIAT, to
produce ammunition for the armored vehicles.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported that Malaysia planned to purchase two
submarines from Turkey to strengthen the combat force of its
Navy.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, with a total of 16 submarines, has the world's
ninth largest submarine fleet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
