<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MOU Ties Guangdong And AT&AMP;T Closer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The US telecom leader AT&AMP;T signed
a memorandum of understanding (MOU) with South China's Guangdong
Province on March 19, to supply the province with technical
support and consultancy, AT&AMP;T representatives announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the MOU clinched by Cui Xun, director of
Guangdong Posts and Telecom Administration, and Art Kobler,
president of AT&AMP;T (China) Inc., the two partners will cooperate on
nine proposed projects, including establishing a provincial-level
electronic data interchange (EDI) network, accelerating broadband
and multi-media applications, optimizing the wireless network,
setting up a call center, and founding an electronic tax-payment
system.
</P>
<P>
Cui told the signing ceremony that Guangdong experienced fast
development in telecommunications industry since China adopted the
reform and opening-up policy in late 1970s, and has launched a
"comparatively advanced telecom network".
</P>
<P>
"It is therefore both necessary and realistic to further
develop applications and offer new services," he said, adding that
the provincial government welcomes such technical cooperation with
AT&AMP;T and other global telecom carriers.
</P>
<P>
John Legere, president of AT&AMP;T Asia/Pacific, said on behalf of
AT&AMP;T that as traditional business partners of Guangdong, "We see
this agreement as an important step in what we expect will be a
long and mutually rewarding relationship with Guangdong."
</P>
<P>
One of the oldest telecom empires founded in 19th century, AT&AMP;T
now operates in 14 countries and territories across Asia and the
Pacific Region, and has joint ventures in China, Australia, India,
Japan and the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
