<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Foreign Currency Reserve Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel's foreign currency
reserves attained an all-time record of 13.974 billion dollars in
February, registering an increase of 1.182 billion dollars during
the month, according to a report of bi-weekly Israel Business
Today.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting figures released by the Bank of Israel
earlier this month, said the reserves had risen by close 2.5
billion dollars, or 22 percent, since the beginning of this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank said that the large increase in foreign
currency reserves is a result of the bank's acquisitions of
foreign currency from the private sector, and from the continued
placement of funds by foreign residents in the country. The Bank
of Israel bought around 1 billion dollars of foreign currency
from the private sector in February, following purchases totaling
1.2 billion in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The country's reserves of foreign currency rose by 5.82
billion dollars since the beginning of 1996 -- a rise of 71
percent compared with the level in December 1995. Since the
beginning of 1994, the reserves have increased by 7.2 billion
dollars, or 105 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Israel's SWAP (shekel-dollar transactions with the
commercial banks) transactions to date amount to 2.2 billion
dollars, which would have brought the foreign currency reserves
up to 16.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The volume of foreign currency transactions with customers
during February reached 6.32 billion dollars, with the mean daily
level rising 8.1 percent to 372 million dollars, compared with
the January daily volume of 344 million dollars. The inter-bank
foreign currency transaction level, however, dropped to 975
million dollars from a January level of 1.65 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
