<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos: Manila Undecided on Claim to Marcos' Deposits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has not
yet agreed on a compromise settlement with the victims of late
former president Ferdinand Marcos on the 450 million US dollar
Marcos' deposits in Swiss banks, President Fidel Ramos said today.
</P>
<P>
"A Cabinet cluster is still working on it," Ramos told
reporters when attending a ceremony marking the 11th anniversary
of the Presidential Security Group.
</P>
<P>
Solicitor General Silvestre Bello, member of the government
panel holding peace talks with the National Democratic Front (NDF)
in the Netherlands, said earlier that the government is
considering an NDF demand to share the deposits to pave the way
for a final peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
The NDF had earlier questioned the sincerity of the
government's peace efforts after it evaded the question of sharing
the Marcos money with some 10,000 victims during the Marcos
regime.
</P>
<P>
Bello said Thursday in a telephone interview that the
government was "inclined to withdraw its claim to the Swiss
deposits."
</P>
<P>
He said the government "will conclude an agreement for the
indemnification of the victims" under the Marcos regime as "an
addendum to the joint agreement on security and immunity guarantee
forged between the government and the NDF."
</P>
<P>
The more than 10,000 victims had earlier won a damage suit
before the Honolulu District Court in the United States against
the Marcoses for alleged abuses committed on them during the 20
years of Marcos' rule.
</P>
<P>
With the decision, the district court had ordered a freeze on
all deposits of the Marcoses in various Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
But the Philippine government, opposing the victims' claim,
said the Marcos estate must first pay its taxes to the government
and asserted its demand with the filing of a probate proceeding
before a regional trial court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
