<HEADLINE> Arab Intellectuals Petition for Peace in E.Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Seven Egyptian intellectuals are
traveling to Israel today to team up with Jordanians,
Palestinians and Israelis for a planned demonstration in East
Jerusalem, protesting Israeli actions in the occupied Arab land.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration is part of a two-day agenda for launching the
International Alliance for Arab-Israeli Peace(IAAIP), a popular
pressure front formed at Copenhagen at the end of January to press
for the continuation of the Arab-Israeli peace process.
</P>
<P>
Members of Israel's Peace Now movement, Knesset members,
Palestinians from across the political spectrum as well as
Jordanians and Egyptians are expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
According to political analyst Lutfi el-Kholi, the Alliance
will initiate a movement opposing Israel's negative policies
towards the peace process, namely the building of Jewish quarter
of Har Homa and the decision to shut down four Palestinian offices
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the East Jerusalem march, the intellectuals and
public figures will also meet with Israeli citizens and talk with
the Palestinian National Authority, in a show of support for the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The trip aims to condemn all actions taken by the Israeli
government which show that it does not respect signed agreements
and the principles of the peace process, as outlined in the
Copenhagen Declaration," said Kholi, who is traveling to Israel
today.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent opinion poll by Israel Radio, about 47
percent Israelis support the Israeli Har Homa construction while
49 percent oppose it.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that if the two-day activities in East Jerusalem
are effective, the credit and legitimacy of the movement will be
greatly boosted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
