<HEADLINE> Tuberculosis Plagues S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government is making efforts to control the increasing
tuberculosis (TB), the Star local daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has to spend 500 million Rands (113 million U.S.
Dollars) a year on TB control, Olive Shisana, the
Director-General of Health was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
TB, the biggest killer among various epidemics in South
Africa, killed 10,000 people and made 160,000 people sick last year,
an official survey said.
</P>
<P>
About 3.5 million new cases were expected by 2005 if current
trends continue, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
To curb the epidemic, the South African government is
implementing the internationally-proven DOTS (directly observed
treatment short course) strategy.
</P>
<P>
However, the TB cure rate in four of the nine provinces in
South Africa has increased by
between nine and 26 percent, according to an investigation by the
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to the DOTS strategy, and to the promise of
curing 85 percent of TB patients by the year 2000," Shisana said.
enditem

=03210818

=03210824
NNNN
16:23 16:23 g # PAB
</P>
