<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Oilfields Still Have Untapped Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The aging oilfields in the
eastern part of China will remain the major oil producers into the
early next century, with the annual oil output forecast at 115
million tons by the year 2000, or 90 percent of the country's
total.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official with the China National
Petroleum Corp (CNPC), the oilfields in eastern China, the output
of which accounts for over 90 percent of the country's total, have
limited the rate of natural output decline to within 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, these oilfields have accelerated prospecting to push
the oil production capacity to 64 million tons, thus maintaining
output.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that by the year 2000, Daqing, Shengli and
Liaohe , three of the country's leading oilfields, will stabilize
their outputs at 53 million tons, 26.5 million tons and 15.5
million tons, respectively.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the annual outputs of the North China, Dagang and
Jilin oilfields will reach around five million tons each. The
output of the Jiangsu Oilfield in east China exceeded one million
tons last year, and it is expected to maintain its growth. Other
oilfields such as those of Zhongyuan, Henan and Jianghan, also
report growth in production.
</P>
<P>
The CNPC official said that by the year 2000 China's onshore
oil output is expected to hit between 145 million tons and 150
million tons, of which some 29.5 million tons will be pumped out
by the oilfields in the western and central parts of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
