<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Elections To Shift Balance Of Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Today's local government
elections in Sri Lanka may see a shift in the balance of power in
the country's local government bodies.
</P>
<P>
In the local government elections in 1991, the present
opposition United National Party (UNP), which was then in power,
swept the polls to win 49.4 percent of the vote and won a total of
193 out of 237 local bodies as against 35 won by the Sri Lanka
Freedom Party (SLFP), the main partner in the ruling Peoples
Alliance (PA) which polled 35.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
On that occasion, the UNP won 9 out of 10 Municipal Councils,
28 out of 33 Urban Councils and 156 out of 194 Village Councils as
against the SLFP's one Municipal Council, two Urban Councils and
33 Village Councils.
</P>
<P>
At the parliamentary elections in 1994, however, the PA won
power and at the Presidential elections that followed, President
Chandrika Kumaratunga, the PA candidate, won a record 63 percent
of the poll.
</P>
<P>
The public believed that the PA is expected to do better and
win more local government Councils at today's elections.
</P>
<P>
However, according to analysts here, the PA will not be able to
retain the 63 percent poll it won at the Presidential elections in
1994 nor will the UNP be able to retain the 193 Councils it won at
the 1991 local government elections.
</P>
<P>
They said that today's elections will witness a change in the
balance of power in the country's local government bodies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
