<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Parliament Approves Pact With Bosnian Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Both chambers of Yugoslavia's
Federal Assembly on Thursday approved an agreement to establish
cooperative relations with the Bosnian Serb Republic singed last
month.
</P>
<P>
Milomir Minic, Chairman of the Citizens Chamber of the Federal
Assembly, said that the historical agreement would not only
strengthen the unity of the Serbs, but also lay a foundation for
the bilateral cooperation in the fields of economy, education,
culture, as well as science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia and the Bosnian Serb Republic of Srpska signed the
agreement on February 28 in Belgrade. Under the agreement, neither
of them will allow its territory to be used for aggression against
the other, and both will make efforts to keep peace and stability
and enhance mutual understanding in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dayton peace accord signed in December 1995,
which ended the three-and-half-year Bosnian war, the Bosnian
Moslem-Croat Federation is also allowed to set up such a special
tie with Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The parliament of the Bosnian Serb Republic approved the
agreement with 61 to 11 on March 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
