<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brisk Polling at Sri Lanka's Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Polling was brisk from early
morning at most of Sri Lanka's 8,248 polling stations where 9.73
million voters will be selecting 3,567 members to 238 local
bodies, according to election officials here.
</P>
<P>
A officer in a polling station in Colombo told Xinhua that from
as early as 6:00 a.m. voters were seen trekking to polling
stations and only the old and disabled were transported in
vehicles to cast their vote. The voting commenced at 7:00 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Officials supervising the polls checked poll cards, marked the
fingers of voters with indelible ink and then issued the ballot
papers.
</P>
<P>
The ballot papers carried the symbols of the political parties
and independent groups which were contesting the polls and a list
of different candidates.
</P>
<P>
Most voters were certain that the contest was mainly between
the ruling People's Alliance (PA) and the main opposition United
National Party (UNP).
</P>
<P>
Some officials at the station believed that the PA, which is
contesting 231 of the 238 councils, will perform better and win
more councils though it may not exceed 63 percent of the votes it
won at the 1994 Presidential elections while the UNP is contesting
all 238 elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
