<HEADLINE> EAC Customs Duties Urged To Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The East Africa Cooperation
(EAC) Executive Secretary, Ambassador Francis Muthaura, has urged
member states to start collecting customs duties at first point of
entry as resolved in August, 1996.
</P>
<P>
He made the urgement in Arusha, northern Tanzania, on Thursday
when opening a two-day meeting of the EAC fiscal and monetary
policies harmonisation committee.
</P>
<P>
"While the momentum for regional cooperation picks up, there is a
need for member states to start implementing the decision already
made", the executive secretary stressed.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura noted that difficulties have arisen in the course of
implementing the decision.
</P>
<P>
He asked the sub-committee to propose a date on which a decision
would be made, adding that the move was meant to strengthen regional
integration process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ambassador also called for the establishment of data
collection and analysis systems to enable member states to monitor
developments towards regional integration.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by officials from the Kenyan Ministry of
Finance and experts from revenue authorities and central banks from
the three-member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
