<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Wins Gold in Men's Event at Figure Skating Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, Switzerland, March 20 (Xinhua/OANA) -- Canadian
skater Elvis Stojko, the gold medalist in the Men's competition
said here today that he won the championship through a tough
competition and by his confidence.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at the end of the Men's competition,
Stojko said that the gold medal is a present for his birthday when
he turns 25 on March 22. "I'm happy and excited about the whole
thing. It's a tough competition and we're all in the same boat. I
have confidence and a set plan. I'm going out with all I've got
and push myself to my limits and challenge myself."
</P>
<P>
When asked about the last-minute withdrawal from the free
program by Russia's Alexei Urmanov, Stojko said, "I didn't know
Alexei had pulled out. I didn't realise his injury was so
severe. I went out thinking everyone was going to put everything
in. It doesn't matter who is there competing. Anything can
happen. Even if I skate clean I have no control over the rest."
</P>
<P>
Talking about his own setbacks, Stojko, of Slovenian origin,
said, "I've pulled myself up from the rough short program I skated
in Edmonton last year, to come back from that, all the doubts and
the negative comments. I'm glad to come back and push all that
aside and focus on what I have to do."
</P>
<P>
At the same press conference, Todd Eldredge from the United
States, the silver medalist, said, "Elvis obviously skated great
and so I can't argue with it. Of course, I'm disappointed I didn't
win but I'm not disappointed with my performance."
</P>
<P>
Eldredge, 25 years old, hoped to compete against Stojko in the
1998 Winter Olympic Games in Nagano, Japan. "I'll give Elvis a run
for his money!" he said.
</P>
<P>
Alexei Yagudin from Russia, the 17-year-old bronze medalist,
said, "Yesterday I was dreaming of being 5th or 6th. My skating
was a big present for me as my birthday was two days ago."
</P>
<P>
On Urmanov's pullout, Yagudin said, "Yesterday, when Urmanov
did his program, he was sore; this morning he said maybe he
wouldn't skate tonight. He's still the leader of the Russian
team."
</P>
<P>
23-year-old Urmanov was the first after the short program
yesterday. He withdrew from the free program competition because
of a groin injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
