<HEADLINE> Cuba Vows no Bowing to Spanish Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto
Robaina today accused as "arrogant, false and meddling" a
statement by the Spanish foreign minister about a Spanish tourist
involved in a traffic accident in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"In the worst style of Yankee overbearing, but now with a
Spanish touch, (Spanish Foreign Minister Alberto) Matutes said he
was studying to recommend Spaniards not to travel to Cuba,"
Robaina told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Matutes threatened to warn Spaniards to stay away
from Cuba, a popular holiday destination, and to mobilize all the
European Union members to demand the release of a tourist who,
Robaina said, was actually in liberty.
</P>
<P>
A month ago, Spanish tourist Jesus Martin rammed and upturned a
motorcycle of a young woman, who suffered serious damage to
her spine, said Robaina.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Martin was once at a police unit to make a
statement, and was now waiting the start of the trial.
</P>
<P>
While Matutes said the tourist was jailed and was still in
custody, the Spanish consul in Havana said Martin was held for
only one night but was prevented by police from leaving Cuba
pending trial.
</P>
<P>
Robaina dismissed the idea that Martin's case had anything to
do with an exchange for a young Cuban man arrested
in Spain for allegedly possessing drugs.
</P>
<P>
"For more than four decades, Cuba has demonstrated that it does
not bend to any pressure or blackmail. If it has not given up
before the biggest power of the world, much less will it do before
the candidates to haughtiness," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
