<HEADLINE> Venezuela's Ex-president Launches New Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's former president
Carlos Andres Perez today launched a new political party and vowed
to lead the country to a political renewal.
</P>
<P>
The party, known as the "Opening and National Participation
Movement," would break the current political structure and obtain
"a free Venezuela for Venezuelans," said Perez.
</P>
<P>
Perez was elected Venezuelan president in 1988 for a five-year
term as the Democratic Action (DA) candidate, but was ousted in
1993 on charges of embezzling 17 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
His new party, explained the former president, would be of
"coordination, without president or general secretary," and would
probably participate in the general elections next year.
</P>
<P>
"I want to present an electoral agenda that means the real
start of a rescue of the Venezuelan state toward the road to
modernization," he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the launching of the new party, Perez still considered
himself a DA leader, saying that his forced exclusion from the
party ranks did not follow the procedures in the DA statutes.
</P>
<P>
On an earlier occasion, he said the new party, mainly backed by
former ministers of his cabinet and former DA leaders, would be
financed through "known" and "unknown" contributions, dismissing
those from economic groups that wanted to impose their control.
</P>
<P>
Perez was put under house arrest in 1993, and then spent more
than two years at his residence in Caracas until September 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
