<HEADLINE> Polish Solidarity Union Members Continue Protests in Warsaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Members of Poland's Solidarity
Union ignored a government offer and entered into their second day
of protests against the closure of the Gdansk shipyard.
</P>
<P>
Despite the heavy presence of riot police, nearly 2,000 union
members took to the street today in front of the parliament
building and the ruling party's headquarters in this capital.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, many from the economically hard-bitten
Gdansk city and the Silesia mining region, stormed the office
building of the Democratic Left Alliance with pots of red paint.
</P>
<P>
They then threw Molotov cocktails at the nameplate of the
party, a partner in the coalition government, over the entrance to
the building, leaving it in flames.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration started just hours after Prime Minister
Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz held out the hope that 2,000 of the 3,700
jobs being shed at the state-owned shipyards could be saved.
</P>
<P>
Cimoszewicz suggested to the Sejm, the house of
representatives, that the more successful Szczecin shipyard in the
northwest could create a new company that would use part of the
Gdansk shipyard to complete an order from the Polish defense
contractor Polska Zegluga Morska.
</P>
<P>
Solidarity Union spokesman Piotr Zak said on Wednesday that
they would listen carefully to Cimoszewicz before today's protest
started.
</P>
<P>
"If Cimoszewicz says anything we consider untrue, we will also
be protesting," said Zak.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, militants from Solidarity clashed with police who
forcibly evicted them from the treasury ministry they had occupied
in protest at the closing down of the Gdansk shipyard.
</P>
<P>
The union accused the government of being motivated by
political spite in letting the yard to go under.
</P>
<P>
Cimoszewicz said the government cannot waste more taxpayers'
money or press banks to bail out the the Gdansk shipyard, which
was in debts of around 154 million U.S. dollars when it was
declared bankrupt in August.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to parliament earlier, Cimoszewicz accused
leaders of the shipyard of endorsing "irresponsible contracts
that each led to losses ranging from 1 to 7 million dollars."
</P>
<P>
Observers said the conflict over the shipyard has taken on a
political dimension with legislative elections due around
September this year.
</P>
<P>
They held that the Solidarity has seized on the issue to launch
protests against wider government industry policy and to mobilize
its supporters before the polls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
