<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum To Conserve and Display Bamboo, Wooden Slips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- A museum, endowed with 35
million yuan, will be built in central China's Hunan province to
conserve and display 170,000 bamboo and wooden slips unearthed
from a 1,700-year-old well last year.
</P>
<P>
The slips, bearing 200,000 characters, are detailed records of
the political, economic, military, cultural, and geographic
situation of Changsha prefecture under the Wu State (222-280)
during the Three Kingdoms period (220-280).
</P>
<P>
The well, three meters in diameter, was actually a cellar which
served as an archive of the prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists say that the slips are one of the most
significant archaeological finds in China this century.
</P>
<P>
The museum, covering an area of 10,000 sq m, will consist of
three parts, a conservation center to store and treat the slips by
a special process, a research center to input the information on
the slips into a computer for further study, and an exhibition
hall to display some of the slips, their historical background and
the excavation of the slips.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
