<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Opposition Demands Release of Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The main opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) today condemned the arrest of four top BNP
leaders and demanded their immediate unconditional release.
</P>
<P>
BNP Chairperson Khaleda Zia said in a statement that the
arrests were made as the government got frightened by the planned
strike on March 23.
</P>
<P>
Four BNP leaders were arrested on Thursday and placed under
30-day detention a day after the party called a nationwide strike
against the government, the first such program since the Awami
(People's) League took power last June.
</P>
<P>
The arrest triggered a violent street protest during which at
least 15 vehicles were damaged and eleven people were picked up.
</P>
<P>
The arrested leaders, including two members of parliament, are
Dr. Khandaker Hossain, Abdul Mannan, Mirza Abbas and Goyeswar
Chandra Roy. All the four were ministers in the previous BNP
government.
</P>
<P>
A press release from Dhaka Metropolitan Police Thursday night
acknowledged the arrest of the four BNP leaders under the
controversial Special Powers Act of 1974.
</P>
<P>
"The arrested have been given one month's detention to restrain
them from activities affecting law and order and other harmful
acts," the release added.  
</P>
