<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Rules Out Unilateral Intervention in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian Defense Minister Beniamino
Andreatta today denied Italy was planning military intervention in
neighbouring Albania to help restore order in the crisis-hit
country.
</P>
<P>
Following talks with Albanian Foreign Minister Arian Starova,
Andreatta quashed growing speculation that Italy would act
unilaterally to send in troops and said any action would be taken
within a European framework.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta said, "At this time, no Italian intervention -- let
alone unilateral Italian intervention -- is in any way planned."
</P>
<P>
He said that both sides agreed that economic, humanitarian and
military aid to the Balkan country would take place through the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
But Italy has agreed to reactivate agreements between its navy
and Albania to allow Italian ships to patrol Albanian territorial
waters to control the chaotic exodus of boats from Albania.
</P>
<P>
Starova also asked for humanitarian aid from Italy, but
confirmed that at present there are no serious food shortages
apart from in isolated areas in the south which has seen most of
the violence and unrest that has gripped the country over the last
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The European Union last Sunday turned down a request from
Albania for military intervention, but sent an assessment team to
the country to report on how the bloc could help restore order to
the country. They have also agreed to send military and police
advisers to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
