<HEADLINE> Armenia Appoints Breakaway Karabakh Leader New PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Armenian President Levon
Ter-Petrosyan on Thursday appointed Robert Kocharyan, leader of
the disputed Nagorno-Karabakh region, as new prime minister,
according to reports from Armenian capital Yerevan.
</P>
<P>
Former Premier Armen Sarkisyan resigned on March 7 for health
reasons after just four months in the job, Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The move has angered neighboring Azerbaijan which has been
engaged in a bitter conflict with Armenia over the mountainous
territory since 1988, although rivalry between the two South
Caucusus republics over the territory stretches back decades.
</P>
<P>
Nagorno-Karabakh, populated mainly by ethnic Armenians, lies
inside Azerbaijan but separatist troops have fought Azeri forces
and driven them out of the enclave.
</P>
<P>
Nagorno-Karabakh declared itself an independent republic in
1991 and Kocharyan, 42, was elected its president in December
1994, although the election was declared illegal by Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
A ceasefire between Armenia and Azerbaijan, two former Soviet
republics, was agreed in 1994, ending the six-year inter-ethnic
fighting which left an estimated 15,000 to 20,000 people dead.
</P>
<P>
But peace talks have stalled, with both parties refusing to
compromise despite international mediation.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijan described Kocharyan's appointment as a
"provocation," the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
"If Robert Kocharyan has been appointed prime minister as the
leader of the Armenian community of the Nogorno-Karabakh region of
Azerbaijan, this cannot be viewed as anything other than a
provocation, not just to Azerbaijan but also to the norms of
international law," Azeri Deputy Foreign Minister Araz Azimov was
quoted by the AP as saying in Azeri capital Baku. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
