<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Government Elections Held in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Under tight security strengthened
by police and army troops, Sri Lanka's local government elections
are being held throughout the country except in the north and east
due to security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Polling started at 7:00 a.m. (local time) today at 8,248
polling stations to elect 238 local bodies.
</P>
<P>
The elections are regarded as a test for the People's Alliance
(PA) government which assumed office in 1994. Twelve political
parties and 136 independent groups are contesting the elections,
but the main battle is between the ruling PA and the main
opposition United National Party (UNP).
</P>
<P>
The PA's main plank during the election campaign has been
allegations of 17 years of misrule by the previous UNP government.
</P>
<P>
The opposition, on the other hand, is using its campaign to
highlight a string of broken promises by the PA government to
bring relief to the poor, to bring down the cost of living, to
ensure media freedom and to abolish the executive presidency.
</P>
<P>
Since early last month when nominations for the elections were
handed in, incidents of election-related violence, including
murder, shooting, assault and arson, have been on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The most serious one occurred on February 11 when government
parliamentarian Nalanda Ellawala was killed in a clash between
government supporters and their opposition rivals.
</P>
<P>
From February 5 to March 19, there have been a total of 1,840
complaints of election-related violence from the seven provinces
where the local elections are being held.
</P>
<P>
The PA has made 751 complaints while the UNP has reported 818
 incidents. Complaints were also made by other political parties.
</P>
<P>
To ensure peace on election day, the government has adopted
many security measures. Over 30,000 policemen have taken up
positions to ensure that today's elections are not marred by
violence.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga appealed to all citizens to
help the government conduct today's local elections peacefully.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever political party you might belong to it is the sacred
mission of all of us to ensure peace and the rule of law and to
create for ourselves and our children a civilized society," she
said in a message to the nation last night.
</P>
<P>
A police officer said that the Inspector General of Police has
given strict instructions to all his men to take into custody
anyone who tries to disrupt the election process or those
attempting to sabotage the vote by provoking voters.
</P>
<P>
Every police station has a riot squad at its command, said the
officer, adding that in major towns like Colombo and Kandy riot
squad manpower is greater, compared to those in remote towns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
