<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Japanese Veterans Included in U.S. "Watch List" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Justice Department
today put a second group of Japanese army veterans on the "watch
list" and bar them from entering the country for their suspected
medical experimentation during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The department's spokesman John Russell said "more than 16, but
less than 20" Japanese veterans had been placed on the "watch
list" for their roles in Unit 731 of the war-time Japanese army or
other medical experimentation cases.
</P>
<P>
Russell declined to identify the Japanese veterans or provide
the exact number, but another Justice Department official said the
second group included 17 men.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the department took its first action against
Japanese veterans suspected of medically experimenting on
prisoners or operating forced sex camps during World War II.
Sixteen Japanese veterans were put on the "watch list."
</P>
<P>
The "watch list" was originally established in 1979 to keep out
people who were engaged in persecution on behalf of Nazi Germany
or its allies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Makes Quads at Figure Skating Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, Switzerland, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese skater Guo
Zhengxin did two quads in the men's free program Thursday night,
the first ever in the history of the world figure skating, his
coach Liu Hongyun told Xinhua after the competition at the World
Figure Skating Championships in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
Guo did one quadruple toeloop and one quadruple toeloop/double
toeloop. "He is the first skater who have ever succeeded in doing
two quads in any competition in the world," the coach said.
</P>
<P>
Despite his historical quads, Guo finished 19th in the men's
competition after placing 22nd in the short program on Wednesday
and 15th in the free program Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Guo is now among the 24 skaters who have qualified for the 1998
Winter Olympic Games in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Olympics, Liu said he would help Guo
strengthen endurance and physical power, in which the Chinese
skater is now somewhat weaker than his opponents.
</P>
<P>
Guo's success has been confirmed by the Figure Skating
Technical Committee of the International Skating Union (ISU) after
the end of the men's free program, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
ISU has announced only three skaters made successful quadruple
jumps in the free program. Elvis Stojko from Canada, the
gold-medal winner, also did one quadruple toeloop/triple toeloop.
The third skater succeeding in the quadruple toeloop is Konstantin
Kostin from Latvia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
