<HEADLINE> Airport at Albanian Capital Reopened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Albania reopened today the Rinas
International Airport here after nearly a week of suspension amid
armed unrest throughout the tiny Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
However, only an Albanian Airlines plane carrying 30 passengers
took off for the Bulgarian capital of Sofia from the facility,
which serves as the country's main gateway to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled flights from this Albanian capital to other countries
will be resumed on Friday, Kapllan Xhabzholli, an official in
charge of the security of the airport, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the reopening of the airport, now patrolled by
security forces and guarded by armored vehicles, will help the
shipping of foreign assistance into Albania.
</P>
<P>
The country's main seaport of Durres will also be reopened
within days, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The airport and seaport were shut down by the authorities on
March 14 as popular protests over the collapse of so-called
pyramid investment schemes turned violent.
</P>
<P>
The government of President Sali Berisha was blamed for
allowing the shady schemes to deprive thousands of families
especially in the more prosperous south of their life savings.
</P>
<P>
A leader of the anti-government insurgents said today that a
50-man commando had been sent to Tirana to "kill" Berisha if he
refused to step down, AFP quoted an Albanian journalist as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, political leaders who are now part of the all-party
government taking the country up to elections by June have come
out against using force to remove Berisha, saying the democratic
process will have the say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
