<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Protests Nicaragua's Human Rights Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Cuba today blasted Nicaragua for
including an exiled Cuban in the Nicaraguan delegation to a
meeting of the United Nations Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
"Cuba will give the right answer to this maneuver at a proper
moment, in a proper place, and in a proper way," Foreign Relations
Ministry spokeswoman Marianela Ferriol told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan government has appointed Luis Zuniga, from
Miami, of the United States, to the Nicaraguan delegation that
will attend the U.N. Human Rights forum.
</P>
<P>
Describing Zuniga as "a two-bit member of the Miami Cuban
counterrevolution," Ferriol said the exiled Cuban was "an admitted
terrorist, chosen from among the gangster fauna of Miami."
</P>
<P>
"Until now it has been the U.S. government as the one
which is accustomed to this kind of show, ... with the only
purpose of attacking us," the spokeswoman added.
</P>
<P>
Ferriol alleged that the United States in the similar conducts
has "appointed poets who have never made a verse, disabled people
who are actually not, cosmonauts and singers."
</P>
<P>
Now, as an assignment, the Nicaraguan government has been
ordered to include Zuniga in its delegation, representing the
Cuban counter revolutionaries, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
