<HEADLINE> Thai Treasury Reserves Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's treasury reserves
dropped by 63 billion baht (2.5 billion US dollars) in the first
five months of fiscal 1997 starting October 1996 as expenses
outstripped revenue, Thai Finance Minister Amnuay Viravan said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the end of fiscal 1996, treasury reserves after allowing for
all obligations stood at 127 billion baht (5.08 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
But the economic slowdown has caused revenue to fall below
target while expenses have grown, forcing the Thai government to
tap treasury reserves to cover the cash deficit, Amnuay was quoted
today by the local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
As a result, treasury reserves for the first five months of
fiscal 1997 stood at 64 billion baht (2.56 billion us dollars).
</P>
<P>
Revenue for the first five months of fiscal 1997 totaled 305.02
billion baht (12.2 billion US dollars). Expenditure during the
first five months totaled 364 billion baht (14.5 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of fiscal 1997, the Thai government ran a
budget deficit of 53.76 billion baht (2.15 billion US dollars).
For the second quarter, a deficit of 16.7 billion baht (668
million US dollars) is expected.
</P>
<P>
But Amnuay maintained that revenue in the second half of fiscal
1997 should increase.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Finance Ministry is predicting a budget surplus of
57.2 billion baht (2.28 billion US dollars) for the third quarter
and 15.3 billion baht (608 million US dollars) for the fourth
quarter. If targets are met, the fiscal 1997 budget would run a
surplus of 2.03 billion baht (81 million US dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
