<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fast Growth of Sino-US Trade Benefit to Both Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The sustained growth of Sino-US
trade, which is the mainstream of the the bilateral trade ties,
has played a positive part in the economic development and
creation of jobs in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made in a white paper on Sino-US trade
balance, which was released by the Information Office of the State
Council here today.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said that despite statistical discrepancies,
trade figures of the two sides both suggested the rapid
development of the Sino-US trade since 1979, when the two
countries established diplomatic relations, signed the ``Agreement
on Trade Relations Between the People's Republic of China and the
United States of America'' and granted each other the
most-favored-nation trading status.
</P>
<P>
The past 18 years since then have witnessed an average annual
bilateral trade growth rate of more than 18 percent, the document
added.
</P>
<P>
The white paper indicated that such rapid advancement of the
bilateral trade was mainly attributable to the marked differences
in the two countries' resources, economic structures, industrial
setup and consumption levels, and to the fact that their economies
can be complementary to each other.
</P>
<P>
Apart from trade exchanges, it said, US investment in China has
also witnessed extensive development. By the end of 1996, 22,240
projects with US investment had been launched in China with a
committed investment volume of 35.17 billion US dollars. Paid-up
investment in those projects totalled 14.29 billion US
dollars. Excluding the regions of Hong Kong and Taiwan, the United
States is the second largest investor in China, next only to Japan.
</P>
<P>
"The sustained growth of Sino-US trade has played an active
part in the economic development and creation of jobs in the two
countries," it said.
</P>
<P>
For the United States, the document continued, its direct
exports to China alone have created 300,000 jobs while bilateral
trade development has created at least one million jobs for the US
industry and service sectors, and such a trend is marked by a
continuous growth from year to year.
</P>
<P>
China's relatively low labour costs have cut the prices of
daily necessities such as shoes, garments and toys on the US
market, and have helped easing inflation in the United States,
bringing practical benefits to US consumers, the white papaer
said.
</P>
<P>
It added that a 1994 World Bank report noted that US consumers
would have had to spend an extra 14 billion US dollars per year if
the United States had had to import similar products from other
countries instead of China.
</P>
<P>
For China, the document noted, millions of workers are involved
in the processing and assembling business for exports to the
United States. This has promoted the economic development of
China's coastal areas. China's imports of some relatively advanced
technological products from the United States also help its
modernization.
</P>
<P>
The domination of entrepot and processing trade in the
bilateral trade has promoted the fast growth of Sino-US trade
volume, but, at the same time, resulted in a relatively large
deviation between the statistics and reality of trade figures of
the two countries, the white paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Exaggerates Trade Deficit with China, Says White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The analysis of statistics has
shown that the size of the US trade deficit with China has been
largely exaggerated by the US side, according to a Chinese
government document released here today.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, it is far from being sufficient to evaluate the two
nations' trade balance situation only on the basis of the trade
statistics of the US side," said the white paper on Sino-US trade
balance, which was released by the Information Office of the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
The white paper noted that the so-called enormous trade deficit
against China under the US statistics in recent years is
attributable to a variety of factors, including flaws in
statistical techniques and methods as well as the US policies
toward China.
</P>
<P>
"It should not shift the blame upon other countries," the
document said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the US side indicate that Sino-US trade had
been in favour of the US side during the 1979-1982 period, but the
United States started suffering from deficit in 1983 and the figure
amounted to 39.5 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Chinese statistics, however, indicate that China had suffered
from deficit in the bilateral trade during the 14 years between
1979 and 1992. Surplus first appeared in 1993 and the figure rose
to 10.5 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The document quoted a report released in 1994 by a Sino-US
bilateral trade statistics expert group as saying that the US
import statistics has ignored entrepot trade and value added from
entrepot trade to over-estimate its imports from China, and the US
statistics of its exports to China has been under-estimated by
neglecting re-exports.
</P>
<P>
The group was set up under the Sino-US Joint Commission on
Commerce and Trade for diagnosing the large difference in the
bilateral trade statistics by China and the United States and the
large US trade deficit against China under US statistics.
</P>
<P>
According to analyses of the group, the white paper said, the
US method in determining the origin of goods also leads to the
discrepancies in the statistics of the two sides, and the United
States has under-estimated its export value to China because of
its incomplete export statistics.
</P>
<P>
On December 5, 1996, officials with the Census Bureau of the US
Department of Commerce pointed out that at least 10 percent of US
exports might have been overlooked in statistics because exports,
unlike imports, are not taxed and do not bring the government any
direct revenue.
</P>
<P>
Since the trade statistics expert group was only in charge of
investigating and analyzing the difference between the trade
statistics published by China and the United States, the trade
statistics methods adopted by the two sides have not been
correspondingly adjusted, and the US side's over-estimation of its
trade deficit against China has not since changed substantially,
the white paper said.
</P>
<P>
It was calculated that the 1996 US trade deficit against China,
as published by the US side, was over-estimated by an amount of
some 16 billion US dollars, the document noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statistics on Origin Cannot Reflect Real Sino-US Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- China said here today that
irrationalities in the trade statistical principle of origin of
goods made the US side seriously exaggerate its trade deficit
against China and distorted Sino-US trade balance.
</P>
<P>
Due to the lack of internationally unified rules of origin,
countries formulate rules of origin according to their own needs,
resulting in different criteria, leaving room for discretion,
according to a white paper on Sino-US trade balance released by
the Information Office of the State Council here today.
</P>
<P>
Currently, both China and the United States calculate their
external trade according to the principle of origin of goods.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said that propelled by fast-growing economic
and trade co-operation among countries in the world today and
increasing cross-border investment, goods exchanged through
international trade are no longer products made by one country,
but ``world products'' whose manufacture involves efforts from
several countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is obviously difficult for the current rules of origin, as
employed by trade statistics, to accurately reflect the main
changes in world economic development," the white paper said,
"These rules could even result in a distorted picture of the trade
balance situation."
</P>
<P>
Processing trade that has boomed in some countries and regions
over the last two to three decades had the problem further
complicated, the document said, adding that processing trade
expansion is a major factor behind China's export growth in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
China's processing trade has developed since the mid-1980s
when investors from developed countries including the United
States and Japan as well as Singapore, the Republic of Korea, and
the Hong Kong and Taiwan regions started to move their
labour-intensive industries or production procedures to China in a
bid to cut production costs and enhance their international
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Dependent on overseas investors' original marketing channels,
processing trade products are primarily sold to their traditional
markets including the United States via entrepot trade through
Hong Kong, and to calculate them according to certain rules of
origin, China -- instead of the investors' home countries or
regions and exporters of materials and auxiliary parts -- became
the exporter, the document said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the document said, more than two-thirds of
US-bound Chinese exports have undergone entrepot trade in the Hong
Kong region. The value added at Hong Kong has been far greater
than that in China's mainland, hence Hong Kong has benefited far
more than the mainland from the processing trade.
</P>
<P>
"If that part of the added value is counted as Hong Kong's
exports, China's trade surplus against the United States will drop
accordingly, or even turn into deficit," the white paper said.
</P>
<P>
The document concluded that while applying the origin-based
statistics, it is imperative to be fully aware of the method's
limitations and discern from the figures the actual benefits of
all trading partners after careful analysis.
</P>
<P>
"That is the only way conducive to removing misunderstanding
and properly settling bilateral trade disputes," it said.
</P>
<P>
The white paper also said that it is a must to note the trend
of increasingly closer international economic links and
ever-growing cross-border investment and service trade that are
growing by the day, and on that ground, improve and perfect the
computing of trade figures so that statistics will comply with
reality and better serve the mutually beneficial co-operation
among countries in the world, and sound economic and trade
development across the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Give Up Claim on Marcos' Swiss Deposits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
give up its claim to the 450 million US dollars in Swiss deposits
of the late former president Ferdinand Marcos in favor of the
10,000 victims during the martial law era, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Solicitor General Silvestre Bello, member of the government
panel holding peace talks with the National Democratic Front (NDF)
in the Netherlands, was quoted as saying in a telephone interview
that the government was "inclined to withdraw its claim to the
Swiss deposits."
</P>
<P>
He said the government "will conclude tonight an agreement for
the indemnification of the victims" under the Marcos regime as "an
addendum to the joint agreement on security and immunity guarantee
forged between the government and the NDF."
</P>
<P>
The more than 10,000 victims had earlier won a damage suit
before the Honolulu District Court in the United States against
the Marcoses for alleged abuses committed on them during the 20
years of Marcos' rule.
</P>
<P>
With the decision, the district court ordered a freeze on all
deposits of the Marcoses in various Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
But the Philippine government, opposing the victims' claim,
said the Marcos estate must first pay its taxes to the government
and asserted its demand with the filing of a probate proceeding
before a regional trial court.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Export Control against China: Major Trade Balance Obstacle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- China said here today that the US
discriminatory export control policies towards China have hindered
US exports to China and therefore have become a major obstacle for
bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese Government hopes the US Government will,
proceeding from the long-term interest of bilateral trade and
economic co-operation, adopt effective measures to relax or even
cancel the current discriminatory export control policies against
China so as to usher in a healthy and balanced Sino-US trade
relationship," said a white paper on Sino-US trade balance,
released by the Information Office of the State Council here today.
</P>
<P>
"This is a realistic way of resolving the trade balance issue
between China and the United States," it continued.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said that Sino-US trade relations witnessed
certain progress in the 1980s when the United States relaxed
export control over China. But, since the beginning of the 1990s,
the United States has instituted a series of new sanctions against
China, many of which involve export control.
</P>
<P>
"This change has led to severe consequences and gradually an
unfavourable reverse of trade balance for the United States," the
document noted, adding " it is hard to say that such a change --
indeed a double-edged sword -- is wise."
</P>
<P>
The US export control policies and lingering sanctions against
China have greatly restricted US exports to China as well as US
investment in high-tech sectors on the territory of the latter,
the white paper continued.
</P>
<P>
The document cited the US export control policies as reason of
failure of negotiation between China and US Westinghouse and
General Electric companies over purchase of equipment for China's
Qinshan Nuclear power Plant (300,000 kilowatts) and the Daya Bay
Nuclear Power Plant (900,000 kilowatts).
</P>
<P>
As a result, US nuclear power enterprises, with enormous
interests, have lost their chance of export to China because of
the US Government control over nuclear energy technology.
</P>
<P>
Such a policy of the US has also ripped US businesses of
potential business opportunities worth several billion US dollars
when China planned to import technologies and equipment for
integrated circuits and programme-controlled telephone
switchboards, according to the white paper.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has lost an average of several billion
dollars of exports each year to China in the recent past due to
such discriminatory policies," the document said. "It makes no
sense for the United States to play up trade deficit against China
on the one hand, and continue its export control on the other."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Trade Enjoys Broad Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 21 (Xinhua) -- The broad prospects of economic
and trade cooperation between China and the United States lie in
"sustainable and balanced" growth of bilateral trade, according to
a white paper.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, titled "On Sino-US Trade Balance," released by
the Information Office of China's State Council here today, said
the Chinese side has always paid great attention to the growth of
the bilateral trade and taken effective measures to increase
imports from the US.
</P>
<P>
The white paper described China's market as "open to US goods
and services," which was demonstrated by the large amount of US
products China has purchased and the continuous expansion of US
investment in China over the past years.
</P>
<P>
"All these have brought US enterprises huge profits." the white
paper said.
</P>
<P>
In commodity trade, according to the paper, China bought 69.476
million tons, or 11.62 billion US dollars worth, of wheat from the
US between 1979 and 1996. China now is the largest buyer of US
wheat.
</P>
<P>
During that period, China also purchased 46.243 million tons,
or 9.56 billion US dollars worth, of chemical fertilizers and 308
aircrafts worth 8.72 billion US dollars from the US.
</P>
<P>
In regards to US investment in China, over 100 of the top-500
US enterprises listed by the "Fortune" magazine have so far
invested in various fields in China.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted the business of US enterprises has been
building up in banking and insurance, shipping services, and
retailing as well.
</P>
<P>
After the signing of the Memorandum of Understanding Between
the Government of the People's Republic of China and the
Government of the United States of America Concerning Market
Access in October 1992, China abolished import control over apples
from the Washington State and wheat from California.
</P>
<P>
China also signed with the US new quarantine protocols on such
imports as pigs, horses, dogs and genetic materials.
</P>
<P>
In April 1994, the two countries reached an agreement on
hygiene quarantine provisions on cherry imports from the
Washington State and imports of relevant species of apples grown
in Idaho and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts, the white paper said, have contributed a
great deal to the development of Sino-US economic and trade ties.
</P>
<P>
After examining the prospects of the Chinese market in the
coming five years, the paper pointed out, "China's economic growth
will offer a vast market for world trade and investment."
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics released by the white paper,
China's imports increased to 138.8 billion US dollars in 1996 from
10.9 billion US dollars in 1978. Its cumulative imports from 1997
to 2000 will topped 700 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The white paper also listed China major steps in cutting
tariffs, phasing out non-tariff measures, realizing the free
convertibility of the Chinese currency Renminbi under the current
account and opening the market of service sectors to foreign
investors, which have been helped to improve China's economic
regime involving foreign interests.
</P>
<P>
Take tariffs for example, according to the paper, a massive cut
in the import tariffs of more than 4,000 tariff lines was
introduced in April 1996, bringing average tariff from 35.3
percent down to 23 percent. China has also pledged to further
lower its overall tariff rate to 15 percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said by the year 2000, China will have
initially established a socialist market economic structure and
built up a unified and standard economic regime involving foreign
interests.
</P>
<P>
These achievements, the paper stressed, will "create better
conditions for the world's business communities including those
from the United States to develop economic and trade co-operation
with China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
