<HEADLINE> Russia Disappointed at Israel's Building of New Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian foreign ministry spokesman
Vladimir Andreyev said today Russia was disappointed at Israel's
construction of new settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Andreyev warned, at a press briefing, that the move by the
Israeli authorities could lead to a halt of the Middle East peace
talks and the worsening of situation in the entire region.
</P>
<P>
On February 26, the Israeli government approved a proposal of
building about 6,500 residences for a new Jewish settlement in Har
Homa of East Jerusalem, which is claimed by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Although the international community had called on it to
reconsider the plan, Israel began implementing the construction
work on March 18 amid a new wave of strong Palestinian protests.
</P>
<P>
Andreyev said that Russia, as one of the initiators of the
Middle East peace process, hoped that all sides concerned would
give up actions that were harmful to other countries.
</P>
<P>
They should try to solve all their disputes through
constructive negotiations in line with the existing peace accords
and the norms of the international law, the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
