<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Team to Scale Mount Qomolangma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 20 (Xinhua) -- A Pakistani mountaineering team
will attempt to scale 8,848-meter Mount Qomolangma for the first
time to mark the 50th anniversary of the country's independence.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani team comprising of 10 climbers will leave the
country for their expedition on March 28, announced the Alpine
Club of Pakistan in a news conference here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The team will set up base camp at Qomolangma early April and
climb the world highest summit between May and June 1997. They
are expected to return to Pakistan by the end of June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The team is led by Nazir Ahmad Sabir, an accomplished
mountaineer who was awarded the president's medal for Pride of
Performance in 1982.
</P>
<P>
The Alpine Club, established in 1974, is a national
mountaineering club to promote mountaineering and mountain-related
adventures in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment the Alpine Club has launched numerous
Pakistani and joint expeditions to major peaks of Karakoram,
Himalayas and Hindukush. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
