<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Dollar Rallies on Greenspan's Words </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar surged today
after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan strongly hinted the
central bank will raise interest rates next week.
</P>
<P>
In an appearance at the U.S. congress, Greenspan's repeated
references to the need for preventive efforts to thwart
inflationary pressure in the economy were viewed by currency
traders as the most strong evidence that the Fed's policymakers
will increase rates at its meeting on March 25.
</P>
<P>
The dollar settled at its high point of the day in New York at
1.6935 marks and 123.75 yen, up from 1.6816 marks and 122.82 yen
Wednesday. The pound weakened to 1.5881 U.S. dollars from 1.5982
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Many traders said they now expect the Fed to raise the federal
funds short-term lending rate next Tuesday by a least a
quarter-percentage point to 5.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The market first saw some sell-off incited by a Commerce
Department report in the morning that showed the U.S. trade
deficit rose 21.1 percent in January to a record 12.7 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late
Wednesday: 1.4525 Swiss francs, up from 1.4432; 5.7100 French
francs, up from 5.6700; 1,692.00 Italian lire, up from 1,685.00;
1.3788 Canadian dollars, up from 1.3764. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Turn Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street moved
mostly lower today after Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan
again hinted a need to raise interest rate as a preemptive measure
to combat inflation.
</P>
<P>
The battered technology sector, however, recovered to some
extent after losing for about 5 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell for the third straight
session, with a loss of 57.40 points to 6,820.28.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly a 5-to-3
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume reaching
496.86 million shares, down from 535.56 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 3.12 to 782.65, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 1.81 to 411.78.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 9.97 to 1,259.26, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 0.24 to 591.55.
</P>
<P>
Bonds initially fell after a morning appearance by Alan
Greenspan at the congress.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond
rose as high as 7.02 percent, up from late Wednesday's 6.98
percent. As bonds recovered later, the yield edged down to 6.95
percent.
</P>
<P>
In another example of the economic vigor, the Labor Department
reported that the number of Americans' new claims for unemployment
benefits rose by 3,000 last week to 312,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
