<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Gov't, Business Agree to Promote Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Seeing central and eastern Europe as
a market of strategic importance, German government and leading
business figures today agreed to further develop economic
relations with countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
After a strategy discussion with leading figures from the
business community today, German Economics Minister Guenter
Rexrodt said that politically, economically and technologically
speaking, the central and eastern European countries with a total
population of about 400 million is an important market for
Germany.
</P>
<P>
"The trade volume with these countries runs up to about 120
billion German marks (about 71 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, and
could be doubled in a few years," Rexrodt said.
</P>
<P>
Economic involvement in central and eastern European countries
has ensured more than 150,000 jobs for Germany, according to the
account of a German economic institute.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure that the new government in Russia will carry on the
reforms," Rexrodt said, adding that German "enterprises and the
federal government should make use of this opportunity."
</P>
<P>
The German economics minister also announced today that he will
pay a visit to central Asian countries like Uzbekistan and
Kazakhstan in the second half of August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2.5 Percent Economic Growth Expected for 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 20 (Xinhua) -- German Economics Minister Guenter
Rexrodt said today that the German economy could still expect a
2.5 percent real growth this year after a disappointing 1.4
percent rise in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The general tendency of economic development in Germany points
to a further upswing," said Rexrodt in a government economic
report published today.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, positive factors which would
contribute to a stronger growth include record-low interest rates,
stable prices, favorable dollar-mark exchange rates, growing
industry orders and production, declining labor costs, as well as
a generally dynamic world economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Senate Ends Effort to Decertify Mexico in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today approved
a resolution that ends any chance for Congress to reject President
Bill Clinton's approval of Mexico's anti-drug efforts.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was passed by a 94-5 vote after the Senate had
held intense negotiations with the Clinton administration. The
measure, as a compromise, attacks both U.S. and Mexican failures
in combating drug smuggling and demands more cooperation while
avoiding harsher steps opposed by the White House.
</P>
<P>
The resolution requires President Clinton to make another
assessment after five months, but it focuses on joint progress
against drug traffickers without the stigma of formally
decertifying Mexico's efforts.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton announced on February 28 a certification of
Mexico as fully cooperative with the United States in fighting
illegal drugs, but it triggered the showdown with Congress.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives voted last week to overturn
Clinton's decision but suspended the step for 90 days to give
Mexico time to make specific reforms. Its action has no effect
unless the Senate goes along.
</P>
<P>
The Senate's decision precluded any move to overturn the
decision to certify.
</P>
<P>
The bill, worked out by senators from both parties in
negotiations, sets up intense monitoring with a new assessment
required from Clinton on September 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly President Proposes on UN Council Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. General Assembly (GA)
President Ismail Razali proposed today that the membership of the
Security Council should be increased from 15 to 20.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, which was distributed among member states
in the form of GA draft resolution, five new permanent members and
four non-permanent members are going to be added to the 15-member
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
In introducing the proposal, Ismail said that three out of five
new permanent members of the Security Council shall be elected
from Africa, Asia and Latin America and the Caribbean region. And
the other two will be elected from industrialized states.
</P>
<P>
With regards to the four new non-permanent members, Ismail said
all of them will all come from developing countries in Africa,
Asia, Eastern Europe and Latin America and Caribbean region.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also touched upon questions of veto powers of
the permanent members of the Security Council. It suggested that
the new permanent members of the Security Council have no
provision of the veto power and that the original permanent
members limit the exercise of their veto power to actions taken
under Chapter VII of the U.N. Charter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
