<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly President Proposes on UN Council Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. General Assembly (GA)
President Ismail Razali proposed today that the membership of the
Security Council should be increased from 15 to 20.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, which was distributed among member states
in the form of GA draft resolution, five new permanent members and
four non-permanent members are going to be added to the 15-member
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
In introducing the proposal, Ismail said that three out of five
new permanent members of the Security Council shall be elected
from Africa, Asia and Latin America and the Caribbean region. And
the other two will be elected from industrialized states.
</P>
<P>
With regards to the four new non-permanent members, Ismail said
they have to come one each from African states, Asian states,
Eastern European states and Latin American and Caribbean states.
</P>
<P>
"The underpinning of this proposal is based on the need to
enhance the representativeness, the credibility, the legitimacy
and authority of the Security Council," Ismail said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the objectives of our exercise is to take steps
that will manifest a qualitative change in all aspects of the
Security Council, so that the council becomes more effective in
exercising its primary role to maintain international peace and
security on behalf of all member states of the UN," he added.
</P>
<P>
He explained that according to his proposal, all aspirants are
expected to declare their readiness to assume the responsibilities
of permanent membership to the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"No one state will become a new permanent member unless another
four in the pattern I have described also obtain the required
majority of at least two-thirds of votes in the General Assembly,"
he said. "The fate of any one is therefore inextricably linked to
the fate of the others, thus preventing a so-called quick fix."
</P>
<P>
The so-called quick fix is advocated by the United States,
which intends to admit Germany and Japan into the Security Council
as permanent members first and then consider the developing
world's candidacies for the permanent seats.
</P>
<P>
In his proposal, Ismail also touched upon questions of veto
powers of the permanent members of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
It suggested that the new permanent members of the Security
Council have no provision of the veto power and that the original
permanent members limit the exercise of their veto power to
actions taken to maintain international peace and security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Steel to Cut Thousands of Jobs in 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 20 (Xinhua) -- British Steel (BS) confirmed today
that it plans "significantly more" than 5,000 job cuts over the
next five years because of the impact of the strong pound and
overseas competition on its finances.
</P>
<P>
The steel giant said that it has to make cuts "as a matter of
urgency" because sales have been hit by the strength of the pound.
</P>
<P>
A BS spokesman blamed the relentless rise of sterling against
the German mark as some 80 percent of BS revenues are related to
the German mark, which has fallen by more than 20 percent against
sterling in the past year.
</P>
<P>
The strong pound is making BS exports more expensive while
allowing foreign competitors to sell more cheaply into the UK
market.
</P>
<P>
But the company is refusing to confirm the exact number of jobs
to go. It will meet trade unions Friday to discuss the
cost-cutting program.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the job cuts, out of a UK workforce of
43,000, will be imposed on management as well as the shopfloor and
will affect several regions with high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Other measures are likely to include sweeping changes to
working practices, a flatter management structure and team working
in plants.
</P>
<P>
The firm has already reduced its workforce considerably, from
nearly 200,000 in the early 1980s to 53,000 worldwide at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Entities Cooperate in Nabbing Armed Robbers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, March 19 (Xinhua) -- Policemen of Bosnia's two
entities have recently cooperated in cracking down an armed
robbery, the UN reported today.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Ivanko, spokesman for the UN International Police
Task Force, said that on February 20, three masked men in military
uniforms broke into a residence near Bijeljina, which is situated
in the Serb republic, stealing over 100,000 German marks (59,600
U.S. dollars) and critically shooting one family member.
</P>
<P>
Serb police believed that the suspects might have fled to the
Bosnian Federation-controlled town of Tulza and requested, through
the IPTF, assistance from the federation police.
</P>
<P>
The Tuzla police later arrested the suspects and on Tuesday
night handed them and a substantial amount of money to the Serb
side, Ivanko said.
</P>
<P>
"This is an excellent example of cooperation between the police
forces of the two entities, a very high level of professionalism,
and we will hope that this will become more the tradition rather
than just an isolated incident," the UN spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
