<DOCNO> XIE19970321.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cameroun's Premier on Nairobi Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Camerounian Premier Peter Mafany
Musonge warned today that the resolutions of Wednesday's Nairobi
summit on the Great Lakes region will be meaningless if the
concerned parties have no will to implement them.
</P>
<P>
However, the discussions at the summit were fruitful, Musonge
said at the Yaounde International Airport after attending the
summit along with leaders from Zimbabwe, Congo, South Africa
and the host country.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi summit was the third in a series of efforts by
African leaders to seek the last solutions to the Zairean
conflicts, he said.
</P>
<P>
The summit stressed that Zaire's territorial integrity and
boundary should be respected, calling for a corridor in the
region for delivering humanitarian aid to the displaced
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Musonge expressed the hope that African leaders will
continue to look for ways to stop the disintegration and
destruction of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the summit in Nairobi, two other summits were held
respectively on November 5 and December 16 with aims to end the
Zairean conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Tutsi led rebels took up arms last October and captured
Kisangany, the third largest city in Zaire recently. They now
have occupied one fifth of the land of the country, vowed to
topple President Sese Seko Mobuto and refuse to cease fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
